<HEADLINE> Space Shuttle Launch Delayed By Failed Data Processor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The launch of U.S. space
shuttle Columbia, which was scheduled on Thursday afternoon, has
been postponed until Friday afternoon because of a failed data
processor.
</P>
<P>
Columbia has two modem-like processors and both must be working
before it is cleared for launch. The two so-called network signal
processors are responsible for sending and formating data between
the shuttle and the ground, and the shuttle and communication
satellites.
</P>
<P>
During testing in Thursday morning, one of the processors
failed to receive data.
</P>
<P>
The launch was aimed at a two-week-long biological experiment
focusing on the human nervous system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
