<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Lifting of Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Thursday called for
immediate implementation of paragraph 22 of the U.N. Security
Council's resolution 687 as a prelude to lifting sanctions against
the country "once and for all."
</P>
<P>
The call was pronounced Thursday in a statement issued at a
joint meeting of the powerful Revolutionary Command Council and
Iraq's Command of Arab Socialist Baath Party chaired by President
Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that it is high time for the Security
Council, when reviewing the sanctions regime later this month, to
effectuate paragraph 22 of the resolution 687 without delay as a
step toward the complete lifting of sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The paragraph 22 stipulates that all sanctions on Iraqi exports
are to be lifted after its dangerous weapons are removed.
</P>
<P>
The statement of Iraqi leadership came as the U.N. Security
Council is to begin a half-yearly review of Iraq's implementation
of relevant U.N. resolutions, which will surely be factored in
before an end to the sanctions can be declared.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed the need for putting into effect this
paragraph "if relationship between Iraq and the Security Council
was intended to strike a balance and keep on the right track."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been cooperative to U.N. inspections of its eight
presidential compounds suspected of harboring proscribed weapons,
which had been at the center of its latest standoff with the
U.N..
</P>
<P>
The is a result of a deal stricken by U.N. chief Kofi Annan and
Iraqi government in February, which defused the crisis over
weapons inspections and averted an imminent air strike against
Iraq by the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. special group of senior diplomats and arms experts
inspected the presidential sites two weeks ago and found no banned
weapons. But this does not prevent further inspections in the
future because of their open-ended nature.
</P>
<P>
The statement said Iraqi leaders thoroughly reviewed the
"unjust" sanctions the gross harm done to Iraqi people as a
result. "Iraq cannot tolerate criminals' manipulating this issue
of destiny any longer. Iraqis' patience proved to be of no avail,"
it added.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi leadership "held those with ill intentions for the
crises that will likely follow, and for the consequent harm the
people of Iraq would sustain, should they object to lifting the
sanctions," it said.
</P>
<P>
The crippling U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq since its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990 can not be lifted until U.N. arms inspectors
certify that Iraq has destroyed all its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
