<HEADLINE> Britain Outlines Strategy for Information Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) - A coherent strategy to help
Britain take the lead in the information age was formally
announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the strategy, Margaret Beckett, President of the
Board of Trade, said a new Information Age Partnership will bring
together leading chief executives from the information age
industries to work with Government to exploit opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The strategy entitled "Our Information Age" sets out the range
of activity underway or planned within Government.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said in his greeting message:
"Our Information Age which offers new opportunities for greater
prosperity, and a better quality of life."
</P>
<P>
In this policy statement, it sets out ideas on how the
Government will act to enable people to take advantage of the new
information age.
</P>
<P>
It is regarded as a co-ordinated strategy which will focus on
transforming education, widening access, promoting competition and
competitiveness, fostering quality and modernizing government.
</P>
<P>
Beckett said: " the statement demonstrates the importance
Government attaches to new technologies across all aspects of
national life."
</P>
<P>
It will help "the UK exploit the opportunities and become a
world leader", she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
