<HEADLINE> ESCAP Session Opens With Agenda to Promote Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The 54th session of the United
Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific
(ESCAP) opened here Thursday with a forward-looking agenda to
promote social and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP's Executive Secretary Adrianus Mooy said in his opening
statement that the session came against a backdrop of
"considerable uncertainty in the region's economic picture with
the crisis in the financial and monetary sector having adversely
affected the growth performance and prospects of several
economies."
</P>
<P>
He told the delegates from 40 Asian and Pacific countries that
their task was "particularly onerous."
</P>
<P>
ESCAP senior officials will meet for three days to prepare for
a ministerial-level meeting scheduled to begin on April 20, with
the theme of "Asia and the Pacific Into the 21st Century:
Prospects for Social Development."
</P>
<P>
Among the issues debated Thursday were the financial crisis in
the Asia-Pacific and its implications for regional economic
cooperation. Access to an adequate supply of capital to finance
industrial and technological development was also of serious
concern.
</P>
<P>
Since mid-1997, a number of the best performing economies of
the region have been facing an acute financial crisis. Despite
commitments of large-scale financial assistance, the crisis
deepened throughout late 1997 and early 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, some delegates said they felt there have been signs of
a possible turn-around in these economies. They underscored the
need to stabilize the financial flows to the developing countries
of the region.
</P>
<P>
Strengthening regional economic cooperation was another topic.
The delegates discussed how to strengthen strategies based on open
trading arrangements to the year 2000 and beyond. They presented
their views on electronic commerce and trade negotiations under
the World Trade Organization agreements and the need for a
diversification of trade and investment of Pacific island
economies.
</P>
<P>
Some delegates pointed out that there is a tendency to bypass
or marginalize the Pacific island developing countries, mainly due
to "logistical difficulties and difference in the level of
development."
</P>
<P>
They suggested some ways to overcome the problems. They include
intensifying trade and investment information network activities,
institutional capacity building for market information gathering
and dissemination on target markets and human resource
development.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also discussed environment and natural resources
development. They stressed that energy and fresh water were two
issues that required urgent attention in view of the high rates of
population increase and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
They called on the ESCAP to develop both national and regional
strategies for energy and fresh water management.
</P>
<P>
The officials will continue their discussion Friday on
socio-economic measures to alleviate poverty in rural and urban
areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-16 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot, Greek Leaders to Consult on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides will visit Athens on April 24 to have talks with Greek
Prime Minister Costas Simitis on the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing Thursday, government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said the meeting aims at further
strengthening common understanding in view of renewed efforts for
solving the protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is set to follow a visit here by U.S. State
Department special coordinator Thomas Miller, who is expected in
town on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Miller will have separate meetings with President Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, who, correspondingly, will
hold consultations with Turkish leaders on April 22-23 in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Presidential emissary for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke,
is expected to visit the island early next month in a bid to get
the Cyprus peace talks back on track.
</P>
<P>
Denktash has upped his quote for resuming negotiations to
settle the Cyprus problem by demanding his Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus be recognized as a sovereign entity.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared in 1983 the
breakaway state, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-controlled south and
Turkish Cypriot-dominated north since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
