<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Seeks to Build Strategic Ties With Pakistan:Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government is desirous
of building a new strategic relationship with Pakistan, visiting
U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Bill Richardson said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who is on a two-day official visit to Pakistan,
made the remarks during his talks with Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the Foreign Office in
the evening, the two-hour talks involved extensive discussions on
global, regional and bilateral issues, including those concerning
peace, security and non-proliferation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
Underlining the importance of Pakistani-U.S. relations,
Richardson said the U.S. government has moved away from the single
item agenda of Pakistan's nuclear program and is seeking to build
new linkages in diverse fields, with particular emphasis on trade,
commerce and investment.
</P>
<P>
In this context, Richardson referred to the preparations
already underway in Washington to examine new initiatives that
could be explored during President Bill Clinton's forthcoming
visit to Pakistan later this year.
</P>
<P>
He also reaffirmed that the Clinton Administration was
determined to find a mutually acceptable solution to the F-16
problem at an early date.
</P>
<P>
He recognized that the continued denial of the planes, as well
as of the money paid by Pakistan, was a serious embarrassment to
the United States and an unnecessary irritant in the bilateral
ties between the two countries. 
</P>
