<HEADLINE> OAU Hails UN Deployment in Central Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU) Thursday commended the United Nations Security Council for
its decision to deploy a U.N. peacekeeping force to the Central
Africa Republic to replace an outgoing African regional force.
</P>
<P>
By sending the 1,350-strong U.N. mission in Central Africa,
the U.N. has assumed its rightful role as defined by its charter,
OAU Chairman and Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said in a
statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. force will be the first U.N. peacekeeping force to be
deployed in Africa in five years, which is tasked to strengthen
security, collect weapons and maintain order in the Central
Africa Republic's capital of Bangui which was hit by mutinies in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The UN force has a pivotal role to play in maintaining peace
and stability in the Central Africa Republic and thereby create
conditions conducive to the holding of elections in September in
1998, the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Mugabe as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The UN force is to replace the outgoing inter-African Mission
for Surveillance of the Bangui Accord (MISAB) which played a
critical role in arresting conflict and anarchy in the country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe described MISAB as "another shining example of Africans
seeking to solve African problems through sub-regional and
regional efforts."
</P>
<P>
MISAB received financial, material and logistical support from
the French government to help fulfill its objectives.
</P>
<P>
President of the Central Africa Republic, Felix Alinge Patasse
has made the request, through UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
for having the peacekeeping mission in the country until the 1999
presidential elections, Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
"It is my hope that the UN Security Council will give
sympathetic consideration to this request," Mugabe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
