<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Says Fear of Euro Groundless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
Thursday said the fear of European single currency euro
"groundless and excessive" and expressed confidence in the
capability of France to adapt to the single currency.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the statement at a press conference in one of his
last moves to push a widely divided National Assembly to vote for
a series of moves for adapting to the European monetary union by
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly will begin the final debates on European
single currency next Tuesday with a speech by Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin. The debates are expected to see sharp exchanges
between those who support the euro and those who condemn it.
</P>
<P>
"People have fear of the change of money. People fear the
collapse of the frontier, the opening of the economy, the
competition, the role of the financial market, the free
circulation of men and, more perhaps, of capitals," said Chirac.
</P>
<P>
Chirac was referring to many parliament deputies of both the
right and the left who are afraid that the adoption of the euro
will result in a loss of national independence in monetary field.
</P>
<P>
"But I consider them groundless or excessive if we are
vigilant and active in Brussels and Strasbourg, and if we are
serious in the management of our national affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also rejected a request by the Communist Party, which is
opposed to the euro, to hold a national referendum on the
Amsterdam Treaty which fixes the deadline of introducing euro.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a revolution, it is a technical adaptation" said
Chirac, adding that the referendum on the Maastricht Treaty
organized by President Francois Mitterand has already given
"legitimacy" to the Amsterdam treaty, the follow-up version of
the former.
</P>
<P>
He said that France has all the trumps to fend off the shock
from euro, such as its excellent education system, infrastructures
and good geographical position.
</P>
<P>
But Chirac also admitted that France has many "handicaps,"
including gigantic public spendings, a persisting bureaucratic
machinery in government, and heavy income taxes.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, France must carry forward its reforms in
social and economic fields, which are "inevitable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
