<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Produces Scant Amount of World Wealth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Africa, with 13 percent of
the world's population, only produced 1.7 percent of the world's
total wealth, according to statistics from the Pan-African
Productivity Association.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Organization of African Unity's (OAU)
labor and social affairs commission this week, the association
said that Africa's gross domestic product (GDP) per capita was
only 620 U.S. Dollars in 1995, compared to a world average of
4,880 U.S. Dollars, the South Africa Press Association reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
From 1985 to 1995, Africa's GDP per capita declined at a rate
of 1.1 percent every year, said Jan Visser, the president of the
association.
</P>
<P>
High productivity was important for job creation because
economic growth was impossible in the global economy unless firms
were competitive, he said.
</P>
<P>
Visser said that the globalized economy should not be seen
only as a threat - it was also a huge opportunity because it
opened markets for African entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
The OAU meeting was presented with a World Economic Forum
report on African competitiveness in which South Africa came the
7th. But compared to 46 other developed countries, it ranked
only the 44th.
</P>
<P>
However, Pan-African Employers' Confederation
Secretary-General Azad Jeetun said there were signs that the
continent had re-awakened, with 19 countries recording growth
rates exceeding five percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The World Band had admitted that Africa was on the way to
sustained growth, said Jeetun.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
