<HEADLINE> US for Balanced Policy on Nuclear Issue in S.Asia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government, while
working for non-proliferation in South Asia, would approach the
issue in a fair, balanced and non-discriminatory manner, visiting
U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Bill Richardson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who is at the head of a high-level U.S. delegation,
made the remarks during his two-hour talks with Pakistani Foreign
Minister Gohar Ayub Khan.
</P>
<P>
On Pakistan-Indian relations and peace and security in the
region, Richardson, who arrived here Wednesday from New Delhi,
said the U.S. appreciated the measures Pakistan had taken to meet
its defense needs, according to a press release issued by the
Foreign Office.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. Administration was deeply appreciative of
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's offer to resume dialogue with India,
and that he had urged the new Indian leadership to respond
positively to it.
</P>
<P>
On the Afghan issue, Richardson expressed his deep appreciation
for the major initiatives taken by Prime Minister Sharif to
promote a peaceful resolution of the ongoing conflict in that
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the U.S. wish to promote a serious dialogue
amongst the many factions in Afghanistan and recognized that
Pakistan had to play a major role in this process.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar said the traditional
friendship between the two countries provided the foundation for
building a new and strong partnership.
</P>
<P>
He explained at length Pakistan's policy in promoting peace and
security in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Pakistan's commitment to seeking peace in South
Asia on the basis of a fair and just settlement of all outstanding
issues between Pakistan and India, including the Jammu and Kashmir
issue which is at the root of all problems afflicting the region.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the U.S. delegation on the latest developments
in Afghanistan and the initiatives taken by Pakistan to bring the
Afghan factions to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
He said it was important to recognize that a settlement of the
Afghan issue could emerge only from the Afghans themselves.
</P>
