<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes EU Position on Ties with Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus government welcomed the
European Union (EU) position on its relations with Turkey,
believing it would help facilitate efforts to break the deadlock
in the peace process in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Christos Stylianides told his daily press
briefing Thursday that "we assess the statements made by Hans Van
den Broek, the EU External Relations commissioner, as helpful in
breaking the deadlock and resuming bicommunal talks."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Washington after meeting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, the commissioner said he had asked the U.S.,
which enjoys good relations with Turkey, to make clear to Ankara
what the offers exactly are that came out from EU's Luxembourg
summit last December.
</P>
<P>
The EU Luxembourg summit declared that relations with Turkey
would improve if Ankara backs efforts to settle the Cyprus
problem, works toward its relations with Greece, improves the
human rights situation and helps solve the Kurdish problem.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said the summit gives Ankara "pretty much room to
capitalize on" and hoped the U.S. is prepared to encourage Turkey
to go in that direction.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus is included in the first batch of countries with which
the EU opened accession negotiations on March 31. This deeply
disturbed Turkish Cypriots, who refused to resume peace
negotiations unless their breakaway state, unilaterally declared
in 1983 in northern Cyprus and recognized only by Turkey, is
regarded as a sovereign entity.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island following a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman expressed hope that international
efforts would help bring about a change to enable a new round of
negotiations to begin and a solution to be reached to the
long-standing problem.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no indication so far that Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash has moved from his intransigent positions,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
