<HEADLINE> Nigerian Party Adopts Abacha as Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nigeria Congress Party
(UNCP), the country's largest political parties, Thursday adopted
General Sani Abacha, the head of state, as its sole candidate for
the forthcoming presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Some two hours after the party's national convention began
Thursday morning in Kaduna, an industrial base in northern
Nigeria, party delegates from across the country agreed
unanimously the normination of General Abacha, said a report from
the north.
</P>
<P>
"General Abacha is invited and should be invited to contest
the fundamental presidential election in Nigeria as a member of
the United Nigeria Congress Party as its sole candidate," a party
leader announced at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
UNCP is the first among Nigeria's five political parties to
produce its candidate for the August 1 presidential polls, the
last step of the military's three-year transition to civil rule
program scheduled for ending October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The other four parties are expected to hold their national
conventions to norminate flagbearers in the next couple of days.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the UNCP convention, according to observers,
just came to confirm reported plans of the party to adopt Abacha
whether the head of state still holds his military title.
</P>
<P>
Only Wednesday, UNCP National Chairman Alhaji Isa Mohammed
reportedly said the national convetion would mainly deal with the
issue of adopting Abacha as its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
There also have been reports that the other four parties are
keen on doing the same.
</P>
<P>
A joint meeting of the five political parties was held earlier
to discuss whether to adopt Abacha as their consensus candidate
for the presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
As the crucial election is approaching, pressure has been
mounting throughout the country demanding the head of state to
contest the election, amidst allegations that these pressure
groups are backed by the government.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, tens of thousands of Abacha supporters held
a successful rally in the capital Abuja to call on Abacha to
contest, while another anti-Abacha gathering in Lagos was
dispersed by police who claimed the rally was not approved.
</P>
<P>
The second pro-Abacha rally took place in the western city of
Ibadan on Wednesday ended with the death of three people when
police and pro-democracy activists went into violent clashes.
</P>
<P>
Abacha's supporters have said earlier that they will hold
rallies to ask the head of state to contest in every major cities
of the country before he announces his intention.
</P>
<P>
UNCP is the largest political party in Nigeria which has won
victories in the elections of local government councils and state
assemblies.
</P>
<P>
Since UNCP has decided to adopt Abacha as its presidential
candidate, the other four parties are expected to follow suit,
observers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
