<HEADLINE> Hussein, Netanyahu Discuss Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Jordan's King Hussein met unexpectedly near their
border on Thursday and discussed ways of breaking the impasse of
the Middle east peace process.
</P>
<P>
The previously-unannounced meeting took place in a hotel in
Israel's Red Sea resort of Eilat near the border with Jordan,
where Netanyahu has been vocationing. Hussein was reportedly
chairing a cabinet meeting in Jordan's Red Sea resort of Aqaba,
just a few kilometers away.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's advisor David Bar-Illan told the Israel Radio the
two leaders took up the issue of the peace process, but he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
This was the first meeting between the two leaders since
Israel's failed assassination attempt of Hamas (Islamic Resistance
Movement) leader Khaled Mashaal in Amman last September. The
operation angered Hussein who ordered a suspension of security
cooperation with the Jewish neighbor.
</P>
<P>
But ties have picked up since Danny Yatom, head of Israel's
state intelligence and spy agency Mossad, who had ordered the
operation, resigned last month.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic activities on the Israeli-Palestinian track are to
resume next week with the return to the region of the U.S. peace
envoy Dennis Ross, and a tour by British Prime Minister Tony
Blair. 
</P>
