<HEADLINE> Angola's First Mobile Hospital Goes into </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Angola's first mobile hospital
has gone into trial operation in Luanda with an aim to offer
services to the Angolan people, particularly those with low income.
</P>
<P>
This mobile hospital, which has been set up with the help of
the office of the Angolan first lady, aims to improve the health
of the Angolans, offerring those with low income easy access to
medical services.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here Thursday, Yamba Garcia, coordinator
of the moving hospital, said that there are six doctors and four
technicians with the medical team.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles have been equipped with laboratory, X-ray machine and
dispensary, Garcia said, adding that they offer services in
paediatrics and surgery and they have the capacity of treating
ordinary clinic patients.
</P>
<P>
With ready equipments and medical technics, the hospital can
offer preliminary treatment for the patients in early stages and
win time for the whole treatment, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to Garcia, the hospital, in its one-year-long trial
operation, will work closely with the Ministry of Families and
Women, medical institutions of Luanda Province and the
authorities of various districts in the province to go to serve
the poor mass in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Garcia disclosed that the mobile hospital has treated 300
Angolan and Congolese patients in the refugee camp in Luanda's
satellite town of Viana. This first public clinic service has
proved successful, he said.
</P>
<P>
While offering medical services to the people, Garcia said,
they will also probe into the medical situation in some areas in
order to work out a longer-term program for improving the general
medical conditions of the Angolans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
