<HEADLINE> Police Confirms Japanese Terrorist in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot police on Thursday
confirmed reports that a leading member of the Japanese doomsday
cult, responsible for killing 12 people and poisoning thousands of
others in a gas attack in Tokyo in 1995, is in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Glafcos Xenos told reporters that Toshiyasu
Ouchi arrived here on March 12 from Russia, where he had been
planning terrorist activities since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the International Criminal Police Commission
(Interpol) has informed the Cypriot authorities of Ouchi at the
request of Japanese police. Cypriot police are cooperating closely
with the Japanese authorities, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that there is no extradition agreement between
Cyprus and Japan, and for this reason, Cypriot police are trying
to find "alternative measures of dealing with the matter."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that police are taking all necessary
measures to make sure that Ouchi will not cross into the northern
part of Cyprus controlled by Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the cult has around 2,000 followers and 20
branches across Japan. Its leader, Shoko Asahara, is currently on
trial for 17 charges, including murder stemming from the subway gas
attack. 
</P>
