<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Shell Moves to Stop Gas Flaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Shell Petroleum Development
Company of Nigeria has announced a major move toward ending
associated gas flaring in its areas of operation in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
A Shell statement issued Wednesday said that the company,
which takes about 60 percent of oil production in the west
African country, has signed a 6-million-U.S.-Dollar joint venture
contract with an Italian firm to this effect.
</P>
<P>
The contract, signed with Nouvo Pignone of Italy on behalf of
the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation, Elf and Agip, two
big-name foreign oil companies, is aimed at fabricating three
modules at the Odidi Associated Gas Gathering Project in the
Niger Delta, southern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The project, launched in 1996, will involve the collection of
80 million standard cubic feet per day (scf/d) of associated gas
currently flared from five oil stations.
</P>
<P>
The gas will then be transported via a low pressure pipeline
system to a central processing facility to be compressed and
conditioned to sales specification.
</P>
<P>
The project, scheduled to be commissioned in the year 2000,
is one of several specifically designed to eliminate
gas flaring from Shell's operations by 2008.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shell flares about one billion scf/d of gas from
its operations, representing about half of the gas flared by the
oil industry in Nigeria and an energy equivalent of some 180,000
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Africa's leading oil producer and exporter, also has
rich natural gas resources. But lack of utilization has led to
waste and environmental pollution through gas flaring.
</P>
<P>
To encourage the use of natural gas, the Nigerian government
has, in this year's budget, decided to reduce the company levy on
enterprises utilizing natural gas from 35 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government has also increased the penalty on gas flaring
by 20 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
