<HEADLINE> International Conference on NATO Held in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Russian speakers had their own
view of NATO's expansion, believing the expansion is not directed
against any specific country, the State Duma press service
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, at an international
conference devoted to European security and NATO held here on
Thursday representative from the German parliament Heinrich Lummer
said NATO's eastward expansion does not imply confrontation with
Russia, as the world will result in redistribution of power.
</P>
<P>
Lummer, member of the Foreign Relations Committee in the
German parliament, noted that joining NATO would be the dreams of
numerous countries that are coming true. He asked rhetorically
"Why did Russia fail to convince its former Warsaw Pact allies not
to join NATO?"
</P>
<P>
At the conference entitled A New Architecture of European
Security and NATO, Jan Peterson, Norway, chairman of the North
Atlantic Assembly's Political Committee, said that Russia has no
right to ban the expansion of NATO which is designed to counter
potential sources of instability.
</P>
<P>
Russian deputy foreign minister, for his part, noted that what
is especially alarming is that certain countries call for revision
of the Russia-NATO Act's provisions on the nonstationing of
nuclear weapons or large NATO units in new members of the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
The alliance chose "the fallacious policy of expansion" to
justify its existence, and "attempts at making NATO the core of
security would imply militarization of Europe", Valery Manilov,
first deputy chief of the General Staff of Russian Armed forces,
noted. 
</P>
