<HEADLINE> UNICEF Boss to Visit E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Executive Director of the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) Carol Bellamy is scheduled to
arrive here Friday on a five-day visit to Kenya, Somalia and
Southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here Thursday by UNICEF regional office
said that she would review UNICEF's humanitarian activities in
the three east African countries.
</P>
<P>
During her visit, the UNICEF boss will discuss with local
leaders a series of issues including the demobilization of child
soldiers and the humanitarian aid access to children and women
caught in the cross fire of civil conflicts.
</P>
<P>
She is scheduled to visit Garissa and Lokichoggio in Kenya and
Barbera in Somalia and to confer with Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi and other top government officials.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Kenya, Bellamy will launch a Private Sector
Fund-Raising Initiative on behalf of children in need of special
protection, which is a nationwide drive to address the plight of
seriously disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued Wednesday in the United Nations, Bellamy
said that UNICEF wants to declare recruiting children into
armies, sending them into combat zones or forcing them into
prostitution a war crime.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 250,000 children under the age of 18 are
estimated to be involved in wars around the world, she noted,
adding that "to allow this to continue would constitute a
complete violation of child rights."
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that inducing children under 18 years of age
into prostitution should also be on the list of war crimes, along
with murder, torture, rape and other forms of sexual violence.
</P>
</TEXT>
