<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief to Tour Africa in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will make a 11-day 8-country official visit to Africa
in May to explain his ideas about peace and development promotion
in the continent, his spokesman announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came shortly after Annan submitted his 21-page
report on the subjet to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
In the report which was made in response to the Council's
request at its ministerial session last September and will be
debated at a session on April 24, Annan analyzed the causes of
African conflict and made recommendations on peacekeeping and
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
During his tour of Ethiopia, Djibouti, Kenya, Tanzania, Rwanda,
Burundi, Uganda and Eritrea from April 29 to May 10, he will talk
to regional leaders about his ideas of his report, spokesman Fred
Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Besides calling on U.N. member states to take measures to check
arms flows to Africa, to eliminate trade barriers and ease debt
burden of African countries, the report also urges regional states
to maintain zero growth on defense budgets and reduce arms
purchases.
</P>
<P>
Matters Annan will discuss include good government, economic
regulations which would encourage private investment and regional
peacekeeping such as the formation and going into action of a
regional peacekeeping team, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"In Rwanda and Burundi, there is on-going conflict, what he is
going to be talking to the leaders about would be ways to share
power in order to defuse the conflict," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
