<HEADLINE> Russia to Bring Cyprus Issue to Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Russia is continuing efforts for
a U.N. Security Council discussion on the protracted Cyprus issue,
Russian ambassador to Cyprus Georgi Mouradov said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nouradov, who had met with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
and Speaker of the House of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou, told
reporters that Russian proposed such a discussion with the aim of
promoting a resolution to the problem.
</P>
<P>
He pledged Russian support for a settlement based on U.N.
resolutions and the two agreements reached between the Greek and
Turkish communities in 1977 and 1979 that call for establishing a
bizonal and bicommunal federation.
</P>
<P>
"Russia's position is that all efforts must be made under the
aegis of the Security Council and between its permanent members,"
Mouradov added.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council must reaffirm that negotiations for a
settlement in Cyprus should take place between the two
communities, and must reinforce the good offices mission of the
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and his special advisor for
Cyprus, Diego Cordovez.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has demanded peace talks
be held between "two states," meaning his breakaway state, the
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" unilaterally declared in
1983, should be recognized.
</P>
<P>
Mouradov supported Cyprus' right to its defenses, saying he
sees no possibility of a war breaking out because of Cypriot
government's decision to deploy Russian-made S-300 surface-to-air
missile system later this year.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government purchased the missiles early last
year. Turkey has threatened pre-emptive strikes if they are to be
deployed on the eastern Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkey landed its troops and took over 37
percent of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in
Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
