<HEADLINE> Representatives for Lockerbie Victims Head for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Representatives for the families of
the British victims of a Pan Am jet blown up over Scotland left
for Tripoli on Thursday to present a plan on ending the crisis
over the trial of two Libyans suspected in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Jim Swire, who represents the British victims, told reporters
that he is carrying a proposal to Libya on bringing the suspects
to trial before an international panel of five judges presided
over by a Scottish judge in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
London and Washington insist that the suspects be tried either
in Britain or the United States. But Libya, fearing that its
citizens will not get fair trial in the two countries, has refused
to hand over the suspects.
</P>
<P>
The 1988 bombing of the U.S. Pan Am flight killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
Robert Black, the lawyer of the families of the victims, said
the current political atmosphere in Britain is suitable for
putting pressure on the British government to be flexible in its
stances.
</P>
<P>
He warned against the possibility of an explosion of situation
unless a compromise is reached during this year to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Swire and Black held talks on Wednesday with Arab League
Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid on the issue.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Abdel-Meguid told a news conference that there
is a "serious dialog that has started and I certainly appreciate
it."
</P>
<P>
"But the decision has to come from our brothers in Libya. This
(the proposal) will be communicated to them. Our objective is
truth and justice and respect of Libya's sovereignty and dignity,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
