<HEADLINE> Multi-national Force to Sprout in Bucharest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Military experts and diplomats
from the Balkan countries are attending this week in Bucharest the
second expert-level meeting ahead of establishing a peace-keeping
multi-national force in South-Eastern Europe, chief of Romanian
General Staff, division-general Constantin Degeratu said in a
briefing on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Discussions so far have tackled technical and organizational
aspects in particular, said Degeratu. The multi-national
force-to-be will be aimed to "secure a stronger contribution from
the part of the regional states to the process of stability and
trust in this area".
</P>
<P>
The Romanian General stressed the force would unfold activities
under the aegis of the UN, for peace-keeping purposes only. It is
not a rapid intervention force, he added.
</P>
<P>
Degeratu said the meeting, now under way, was largely a
military one, gathering military experts and also diplomats in the
foreign ministries from states seeking to join the force, Albania,
Bulgaria, Greece, Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, Turkey
and Romania, participating are also observers from Italy and the
United States, said Degeratu. Slovenia, which had voiced special
interest in participating in the meeting, could not attend due to
circumstances beyond control.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of this kind was held in Ankara over March
16-18 this year. It was at the meeting that the countries had
agreed in principle to create a multinational peace force in the
Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
