<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief On Lessons of Peacekeeping in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (xinhua) -- The United Nations
peacekeeping in Africa could achieve much if "deployed with a
credible deterrent capacity, equipped with appropriate resources
and backed by sufficient political will", UN Secretary-General
kofi Annan stressed on Thursday in his report on Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Annan said the credibility of the United Nations
in Africa to a great extent depends on the international
comminity's willingness to act and to explore new means of
advancing the objects of peace and security on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said it is important that the United
Nations experience in Africa re-examined and lessons extracted can
guide it for the future.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said the international community's perception of
peacekeeping has been greatly shaped by the United Nations
experience in Somalia, with the memories of that operation
continuing to hobble the United Nations capacity to respond
swiftly and decisively to crises.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations Operation in Somalia was the
first United Nations operation to be withdrawn by the Security
Council before completing its mission.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General said hundreds of thousands of lives were
lost in the course of the genocide in Rwanda that was perpetrated
in full view of the international community. That experience
highlighted the crucial importance of swift intervention in a
conflict and of political will to act in the face of a
catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said the horrifying suffering of the Rwandan
people sends the clear and unmistakable message that the
international community must never again tolerate such inaction.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations experience in Mozambique showed
that in the right circumstances, peacekeeping operation can offer
a flexible and uniquely adapted means to confront conflict in
Africa. Its success testifies to the contribution that the United
Nations can make as an impartial and legitimate actor for peace.
It also indicates the Organization's potential to strengthen and
direct international engagement within a conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said the successive United Nations deployments in Angola
have shown the vital role that can be played by a United Nations
operations sustaining a peace process in even the most adverse
circumstances, but they also indicated the crucial need for
realistic peace agreements, and the importance of having a
credible deterrent capacity within a peacekeeping operation in
situations that remain dangerous and volatile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Calls for Lifting Sanctions against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Thursday called on the United States to lift its
sanctions against Cuba, the Zambia News Agency ZANA reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when meeting a Cuban parliamentary
delegation at the State House here.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also expressed his admiration for Cuba's determination
to stand on its own despite the political and economic problems
that the country has gone through.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also paid tribute to Cuba for its continued assistance
to Zambia especially in the educational and medical fields.
</P>
<P>
"The transfer of manpower resources in the education and
medical fields is much better than aid which looks like charity,"
said the president.
</P>
<P>
He further expressed Zambia's determination to overcome its
political and economic problems through reforms.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, Chiluba said, is willing to learn from other
democracies so that it can sustain its newly-found democracy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the same occasion, Cuban parliamentary delegation
leader Luis Abreu Mejias said his country has encountered a
number of problems since the revolution started in the late
1950s.
</P>
<P>
Cuba is now "committed to establishing a society which caters
for all the needs of the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
ZANA, however, did not give more details about the
delegation's visit. 
</P>
