<HEADLINE> Rubin: Japan's Economic Growth Key to Asia Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Full recovery in financially
troubled Asia cannot be achieved without Japan's efforts to pull
its economy from recession, warned U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the welcome signs of stability now emerging (in
Asia)... we must guard against complacency," Rubin told the
Interim Committee, a policy-setting committee of the 182-nation
International Monetary Fund, which is holding its 50th meeting in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Japan, the world's second largest economy, accounts
for more than half of Asia's output. It "must generate substantial
growth to help maintain a growing world economy and to absorb a
growing share of imports from emerging markets."
</P>
<P>
He also urged nations, such as South Korea, Thailand and
Indonesia, whose financial systems have been rescued with more
than 100 billion U.S. dollars from the IMF, to stick to their
reform programs.
</P>
<P>
British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown said that the
IMF must be modernized to keep up with fast-changing economic
markets.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the agency needed to be more forceful in exposing
risky economic practices of member countries and should also
establish an outside unit of experts to audit its performance.
</P>
<P>
IMF discussions were held following a meeting Tuesday of the
Group of Seven industrial countries -- Japan, Germany, Britain,
France, Canada and Italy.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 said in a statement that the challenges facing Japan
are serious and have intensified in recent months and urged Japan
to "implement quickly a strong program" of economic stimulus.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 indicated their support of Japan's effort to protect
its currency from excessive depreciation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
