<HEADLINE> Resolution on ACP-EU Ties Approved in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's parliament, the
House of People's Representatives, Thursday approved a resolution
on relations between African, Caribbean and Pacific countries
(ACP) and the European Union (EU) beyond the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, the resolution
recognizes the contribution of the Lome Convention to the
economic, political, social and cultural development of ACP and
observes that the future ACP-EU cooperation constitutes one of
the effective and coherent frameworks for facilitating the
achievement of the ACP's socio-economic development projects.
</P>
<P>
Although there are certain groups rejecting the necessity of
the Lome Convention after the establishment of the World Trade
Organization, Speaker of the House Dawit Yohannes noted that "We
are on the side of those groups which support the continuation of
the Lome Convention."
</P>
<P>
The resolution on the ACP-EU relations will be submitted to
the ACP-European Parliament Joint Forum at Port Louis, Mauritius
scheduled on April 19 to 23.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the House Thursday also approved a resolution on
issues of debt cancellation and rescheduling.
</P>
<P>
Africa's economic performance has for long been very sluggish
due to political instability, ethnic conflicts and the vagaries
of weather, said the resolution, adding that the international
community is expected to make a more flexible stance and to
ensure the availability of adequate resources to alleviate the
debt problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
