<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank: Life in Developing Countries Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- People in the developing
countries are healthier, better fed and more educated than ever
before, but progress is uneven, according to World Bank's report
of key development facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
The report, World Development Indicators 1998, said that since
1970, people's living standards have risen dramatically. Life
expectancy has risen by 10 years, infant mortality has nearly
halved; food production has outpaced population growth; illiteracy
has dropped by a third and most children, and more girls, are
enrolled in primary school.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in the period 1965-96, the world's
fastest-growing economy was Botswana with per capita income growth
of 9.2 percent, followed by South Korea and China with 7.3 percent
and 6.7 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The world bank predicts that growth in developing countries
will continue until the end of the century, rebounding from the
temporary setback of the Asian financial crisis, as long as key
reforms, mounted in response to the crisis, are successful.
</P>
<P>
Using both long-term and 1995-96 data on average annual growth
in GNP, and estimates of 1997 growth for 37 developing countries,
the bank said, low and middle-income countries significantly
exceeded their long-term growth rates in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
It noted, low-income countries grew at an average annual rate
of 8.0 percent in the year, compared to 5.3 percent from 1965-96.
For middle income countries, the rates were 3.7 percent in 1995-96
and 3.3 percent from 1965-96.
</P>
<P>
In Sub-Saharan Africa, annual growth averaged 2.7 percent from
1965-96, but increased to 4.8 percent in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates of 1997 economic performance for 37
selected developing countries show that the fastest-growing
economies were China (9.0 percent) and Argentina (7.8 percent).
The worst performance was in Bulgaria (-7.4 percent) and Morocco
(-2.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
The Bank noted that while some regions are making huge strides
in improving the quality of life for their inhabitants, others
still show high infant mortality, poor nutrition, illiteracy, and
too many people living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
It said, infant mortality rates in Sub-Saharan Africa are well
above those found in East Asia 25 years ago, and in South Asia,
gender disparities in education mean that many more boys attend
primary school than girls.
</P>
<P>
The report also listed the international community adopted
targets for improving the lives and the environment of people in
developing countries by 2015.
</P>
<P>
The goals includes: halving the numbers of people living in
extreme poverty, achieving universal primary education in all
countries, reducing infant and child mortality by two-thirds, and
maternal deaths by three-quarters, achieving gender equality in
primary and secondary education, providing universal access to
reproductive health services, and reversing current global and
national los of environmental resources.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the goals could be achieved with right
policies in the developing countries. But the donor countries and
international development agencies must support those developing
countries that show determination to meet the challenge of the new
goals.
</P>
<P>
The Bank said, international agencies must take the lead in
helping developing countries boost their ability to monitor their
progress in reducing infant and maternal deaths or ensuring better
access to primary schools for young girls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
