<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housing Construction Starts Decline in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. housing construction
dipped in March from a 10-year high the month before but still
remained comparatively strong, the Commerce Department reported
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The builders started construction of new housing units at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.59 million, down 2.8 percent
from February, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
It was the seventh consecutive month that new housing starts
exceeded 1.5 million, the longest growth in nearly 11 years.
Despite the decline in March, starts for the first three months of
this year were 9.9 percent higher than the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Single-family housing starts fell 2.4 percent in March to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.24 million. Apartment
building starts declined 3.8 percent to 352,000 units.
</P>
<P>
By region, starts dropped 29.7 percent in the Northeast to a
rate of 142,000. They slipped 7.1 percent in the Midwest to
338,000 and 1.1 percent in the South to 718,000, but picked up
14.3 percent to 392,000 in the West.
</P>
<P>
Housing permits, a leading indicator of future building plans
declined 2.5 percent to a rate of 1.58 million in March.
</P>
<P>
The trend was attributed to high consumer confidence and low
mortgage rates. Consumer confidence is near its highest level in
three decades because of the lowest inflation apart from food and
energy in more than 30 years and an unemployment rate near a
24-year low.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, mortgage rates, which is at just above 7 percent for
a 30-year, fixed-rate loan, haven't been substantially lower since
the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report released today, the Labor Department said
first-time claims for unemployment benefits plunged 22,000 last
week to 289,000, the best in nine months. The level may be
unnaturally low because of difficulties adjusting for reduced
activity during the Easter and Passover holidays. However, it
indicates strong demand for labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
