<HEADLINE> Austrian FM Hopes Cyprus Peace Talks to Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Vice-Chancellor and
Federal Minister for Foreign Affairs, Wolfgang Schussel, Thursday
expressed the hope that the present deadlock in settling the
Cyprus problem will be removed.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark at a press conference after official
talks with his Cypriot counterpart, Ioannis Kasoulides, during
which they discussed the latest developments in Cyprus problem
and Cyprus' European Union (EU) course.
</P>
<P>
Schussel expressed strong support to U.N., U.S., British and
other efforts to settle the protracted Cyprus question, and
stressed the need for "new formulas to bring the two
communities together."
</P>
<P>
The Austrian minister said a Cyprus solution should be
based on U.N. Security Council resolutions and added it could
be possible to reach a bicommunal federal solution, with one
sovereign state and civil citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the present deadlock in the peace process
could be lifted and we will do our utmost to support the
possibilities of hope in the future," he reassured.
</P>
<P>
Schussel described U.N. efforts, European Union (EU) accession
talks with Cyprus and EU relations with Turkey as the three
factors that could facilitate a settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian official welcomed President Glafcos Clerides'
invitation to the Turkish Cypriot community to nominate
representatives in the Cyprus official team that will carry
out accession talks with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Schussel expressed the view that the door should be open
to Turkish Cypriots as long as the EU talks with Cyprus
are taking place.
</P>
<P>
"We want to have the unified island in the EU. This is
a common hope and we should do our utmost to facilitate this
possibility," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has turned down
the invitation and refused to join the Cypriot team for EU
accession talks.
</P>
<P>
He also refused to participate in peace negotiations for a
Cyprus settlement in protest against the EU's decision to have
membership talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Asked about EU relations with Turkey, the Austrian minister
said Turkey is eligible for membership and expressed hope that
conditions could be created so that Turkey "could enter in a
new strategy" with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Cypriot government decision to deploy
Russian-made S-300 missiles, Schussel said that during his talks
here he reiterated "the common concern of all EU member
states."
</P>
<P>
He added that they believe the deployment of the S-300s
could bring new threats, new tensions to the region, but said
the right of Cyprus to have a safe defense cannot be
disputed.
</P>
<P>
His Cypriot counterpart reiterated the Cypriot government's
position that if demilitarization is agreed by the other side or
if meaningful negotiations between the two sides are taking
place, it would not deploy the defense missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Schussel's two-day visit to the island comes only three
months before Austria takes over the rotating presidency of the
EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
