<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Hold Local Elections in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon announced on Thursday that
it will hold local elections in May, the first such elections
since 1963, the official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7,662 members of 646 municipalities, 2,041 mayors
and 3,693 counselors in 1,282 towns and villages will be elected,
Lebanese Interior Minister Michel Al-Murr told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the polls are set to take place on May 24, 31
and June 7.
</P>
<P>
Al-Murr said that 20,142 public servants will be assigned to
oversee the balloting in 10,071 polling stations across the
country except the Israeli-occupied south.
</P>
<P>
There are 80 municipalities and 150 towns in the border enclave
with an area of 1,200 square kilometers, where Israel set up a
self-styled security zone in 1985 with the claimed aim of
protecting its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Al-Murr said that a committee will be formed within five days
to deal with complaints over possible fraud or unfairness in the
pollings in an effort to ensure honest elections.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hopes that journalists and lawyers will be engaged
in the preparations for the forthcoming elections in coordination
with the committee to play a role in monitoring the voting.
</P>
<P>
He also promised that the government will take a neutral stand
during the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
