<P>
Wouter Raemdonck, director of the Luanda Refinery, told the
press Thursday that the investment will be used in importing and
installing new equipment and raw materials, including a steam
boiler and equipment for a newly-built diesel powered plant.
</P>
<P>
The renewal of the equipment in the refinery, he said, is
aimed to promote production and make full use of the fuel. At
present, he added, the production capacity of the refinery is six
tons of crude oil per day merely.
</P>
<P>
Luanda Refinery, the only refinery in the country, was founded
over 30 years ago. With more new oil fields discovered in
Angola, which has brought the country's daily oil production from
600,000 barrels in 1996 to the current 750,000 barrels, the
refinery could hardly meet the national needs.
</P>
<P>
In addition to expanding the capacity of the Luanda Refinery,
the Angolan government is also plann to construct a new
refinery in Lobito, a coastal city in central Angola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
