<HEADLINE> Turkey, Bulgaria, Romania Agree to Fight Organized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey, Bulgaria and Romania
signed an agreement on Thursday to coordinate their fight against
organized crimes, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after Suleyman Demirel, Petar
Stoyanov and Emil Constantinescu, presidents of the three
countries, held a one-day summit in Turkey's Mediterranean city of
Antalya.
</P>
<P>
The three Balkan nations made it clear that they will join
hands in combating drug trafficking, money laundering and illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
The judicial and police departments of the three countries will
set up an effective mechanism of cooperation in dealing with the
matters, the agreement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the organized crimes have reached an alarming
level due to certain political and economic elements and the
special geographic location of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the three presidents also discussed the
possibility of jointly fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that a Balkan peace force should be formed
in a bid to cope with any unexpected and emergent situations in
the region.
</P>
<P>
The Antalya meeting marked another positive step in enhancing
relations of the three countries and will give an impetus to the
cooperation in the whole Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
A similar summit was convened in Bulgaria's coastal city of
Varna last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
