<HEADLINE> Botha's Trial Postponed to June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
president P. W. Botha's trial on charges of defying a Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) subpoena was postponed Thursday
to June 1, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The postponement will enable his lawyers to access additional
documentation introduced by the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
But Botha complained about the delay, saying in a statement
that he found it unacceptable that the case was delayed as a
result of unsubstantiated allegations having been made.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer, Ernst Penzhorn, told reporters that Botha wanted
to settle the case as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The only witness the court has called so far was TRC Executive
Secretary Paul van Zyl, who testified Thursday that more than
2,000 people claimed to have been tortured in police stations
around the country between 1980 and 1989.
</P>
<P>
In light of these allegations, the TRC wanted to question
Botha about whether torture was state policy or was tolerated by
his government.
</P>
<P>
TRC research indicated that incidents of torture increased
sharply when a state of emergency was declared in 1986. The TRC
wanted to ask if there was a correlation between the state of
emergency and torture, and whether there were safeguards to
prevent it, van Zyl said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted from the minutes of a former State Security Council
meeting at which Botha said he was convinced the brain behind the
unrest situation was to be found within the country and had to be
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
TRC Chairman Desmond Tutu is supposed to be the next witness
when the trial resumes in June, Penzhorn said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
