<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: U.S. Leads World in Gun Deaths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States has the
highest rate of gun deaths among the world's 36 richest nations, a
government study found.
</P>
<P>
The rate for gun deaths in 1994 was 14.24 per 100,000 people,
according to the study by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study used 1994 statistics supplied by the 36 countries. Of
the 88,649 gun deaths reported by all the countries, the United
States accounted for 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study found that Brazil ranked second with 12.95 deaths per
100,000, followed by Mexico with 12.69, Estonia with 12.26 and
Argentina with 8.93.
</P>
<P>
Japan, where very few people own guns, averages 124 gun-related
attacks a year, and at 0.05 death per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
The study found that gun-related deaths were five to six times
higher in the Americas than in Europe or Australia and New Zealand
and 95 times higher than in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The study would not specify the reason of the death rates, but
other researchers said easy access to guns and society's
acceptance of violence are part of the problem in the United
States, the Associated Press noted.
</P>
<P>
"If you have a country saturated with guns -- available to
people when they are intoxicated, angry or depressed -- it's not
unusual guns will be used more often," said Rebecca Peters, a
Johns Hopkins University fellow specializing in gun violence.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there are about 190 million private guns
in the United States, nearly one per person. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
