The Sudanese-Egyptian talks are taking place in accordance with
directives given by Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak for normalizing ties between the two
countries, Sudanese Foreign Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese and Egyptian governments should overcome the
differences between them and make efforts to solve the border
disputes caused by colonialism, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese foreign minister described the differences between
the two sides as "summer clouds which will soon be clear."
</P>
<P>
He asserted that the Sudanese government will cooperate with
the 16-member Egyptian delegation led by Ambassador Fouad Ahmed
Youssef.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been strained after
Egypt accused Sudan of involvement in an assassination attempt on
President Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia in 1995. Sudan denied
the charge.
</P>
<P>
Sudan later confiscated all Egyptian properties in the country,
including 120 guest houses, a university and 11 secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
Recently, ties between the two have began to improve. Sudanese
President al-Bashir instructed on March 14 to return the seized
properties to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese foreign minister held talks with Mubarak and his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa last month. 
</P>
