<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Finds Violence Up on TV Shows in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Prime-time television in the
United States is getting more violent, according to a new survey
issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About two-thirds of prime-time network and basic cable channel
programs shown in June 1997 contained violent scenes, compared
with about half of such programs in October 1994, researchers from
four universities found.
</P>
<P>
Across the entire broadcast and cable schedules, the share of
programs containing violence remained about the same, 61 percent,
over the 32-month period.
</P>
<P>
Pay cable networks televised the highest percentage of programs
with violent content, averaging 92 percent since 1994, the study
found.
</P>
<P>
The study, the largest of its kind, was commissioned by the
National Cable Television Association. It was based on a sample of
10,000 hours of programs on 23 channels, including cable and
broadcast, from October 1994 to June 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the researchers said that they did consider the context in
which violence occurs. Not all violence on TV is bad, researchers
said. Depictions that show the negative effects of violence are
good and socially responsible.
</P>
<P>
The study concluded that age-based TV ratings do not provide
adequate information about the presence of violent content in
shows.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD Crowns Schroeder as Chancellor Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) Friday formally elected Gerhard Schroeder
as its candidate to challenge Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the
national elections in September this year.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was confirmed by an overwhelming majority of 93
percent of the vote at a special SPD party congress in the eastern
German city of Leipzig.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, the 54-year-old premier of the western German Lower
Saxony state, has emerged as the greatest hope for the leftist
SPD, which has been in opposition for 16 years, to defeat Kohl in
the national elections on September 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
Declaring "the Kohl era is over," Schroeder told the 515
delegates at the congress that the SPD was now ready to take over
the German leadership to face challenges in a new century.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to make job creation the top priority of a SPD-led
government and to take a pragmatic approach to address the
problems now faced by Germany.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has been widely seen as the most dangerous SPD
challenger to Kohl since the 1980s because he has more chances to
win vital centrist votes much needed by Kohl's centre-right ruling
coalition. He has also been leading Kohl in popularity in almost
all opinion polls over the past one year.
</P>
<P>
As an active proponent of high-technology investments and a
former board member of Germany's largest carmaker Volkswagen AG,
Schroeder often says that he understands the challenges faced by
German businesses in global markets and pledges to undertake
reforms to improve Germany's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
And as one of five children raised by a war widow who earned a
living as a cleaning lady, Schroeder also says he wants to promote
social justice at a time when Germany faces a post-war record
unemployment of about 4.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
With Schroeder as the SPD chancellor candidate, German
commentators are now predicting a much harder re-election battle
for Kohl who is already the longest-serving European political
leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
