<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Specialists Address China's IPR Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April (Xinhua) -- China is playing an emerging role in
the global intellectual property rights protection, a US IPR
specialist said here today.
</P>
<P>
"In terms of patent area, we have been very happy with the
progress in China," Lois Boland, an official with the US Patent
and Trademark Office, said "we even got some anecdotal evidence
from our companies operating here in this respect."
</P>
<P>
"The new title of the China Patent Office into the State
Intellectual Property Office is a very good development because it
will not only influence greatly on patents of trademarks but also
seem to embrace copy right policy," said the professor of law at
George Washington University's National Law Center.
</P>
<P>
"The training center recently established by the Chinese side
is something many of us from the developed countries are very
jealous of," Boland said.
</P>
<P>
SIPO set up China Intellectual Property Training Center two
days ago to train senior IPR professionals for the country.
</P>
<P>
"People from all regions of China are able to have the training
there as well as in other countries, it will be a benefit to
China," said Boland, who had supported the PTO's efforts in the
US-Japan bilateral negotiations and Uruguay Round implementing
legislation.
</P>
<P>
"Although the whole legislative structure is good, we're going
to wait and see down the road as to how those laws are enforced in
China," Boland said.
</P>
<P>
"I've heard good reports at least in the patent area that
enforcement is going very well," she added.
</P>
<P>
In an interviewed with Xinhua, Gao Lulin, SIPO's Commissioner,
said, "China now has a world-leading and integrated legislative
system on IPR."
</P>
<P>
"Although the country has only experienced IPR system for no
more than 20 years, we have been greatly appreciated by lots of
foreign countries and international groups because of our
achievements," he said, "They all regard China as a best worker
and enforcer in the field, even better than some developed
countries."
</P>
<P>
A well-known Chinese IPR expert, Gao also assumes a
high-ranking post in WIPO. "The IPR system is suitable to the
market economy," he said, "and it encourages common people's
creation and invention."
</P>
<P>
"The cooperation between China the United States will not only
spur their IPR development but also produce a positive effect on
the world," Gao pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
