<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Washington Insist on Unconditional Dialogue in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott have reasserted
a western demand for unconditional dialogue between Belgrade and
Kosovo-Albanian leaders with the participation of an international
mediator, the German foreign ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
During their Friday meeting in Bonn, Kinkel and Talbott
stressed that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had so far
failed to meet the demands made by the six-nation contact group at
their latest meeting on March 25 in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
According to the German foreign ministry, Kinkel and Talbott
had agreed that the contact group, consisting of Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States, would move to impose
new punitive measures on Belgrade if Milosevic still refused to
put forward a trustworthy offer for dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Being wary about foreign intervention in the Kosovo conflict,
the Yugoslav parliament decided earlier to hold a referendum on
whether to involve a third party in a political dialogue over the
future status of Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
