<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Urges N.Irish People to Approve Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
on Friday urged the people of Northern Ireland to approve the
peace agreement reached last Friday to end the 30-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said on BBC radio that the success of the historic peace
accord depended on the support of the people in the province. A
referendum on the agreement will be held in Northern Ireland and
the Irish Republic on May 22.
</P>
<P>
"You have got to decide that you are going to enter into this
architecture of peace, if you like, and make it work. If people do
that, it will work," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Blair fell short of asking people to vote "yes" in the
referendum, but said people must make up their own mind.
</P>
<P>
"What we put together was a design for the architecture of
peace. We haven't yet constructed the building. The design I think
is a good one," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"If one part of the building collapses, then the rest of it
will collapse. So it is either mutually assured success or
mutually assured destruction and that is the choice that people
have got to make," he added.
</P>
<P>
A British government spokesman said finance minister Gordon
Brown would visit the province ahead of the referendum and
announce an aid package to support the deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
