<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tornados Kill 11 in Southern United States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Tornados ripped across
southern United States on Thursday, killing at least 11 people and
injuring more than 100.
</P>
<P>
The tornados began early Thursday morning, destroying over 500
houses and knocking out power and telephone services for thousands
of customers. By Friday morning, six people had been killed in
Tennessee, three in Kentucky and two in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said at least 100 people were
injured in Nashville, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
The severe weather cropped up in the Midwest late Wednesday,
sweeping from Illinois into Arkansas and Tennessee. Twenty-four
hours later, tornados had caused damage from Michigan to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
More than a dozen tornado warnings were issued in Alabama,
where 33 were killed by a strong twister on April 8.
</P>
<P>
The storms swept through northern Georgia late Thursday and
early Friday morning, causing floods and leveling houses, trailers
and barns. Four minor injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
The tornados were the latest in a string of deadly storms,
which have killed more than 100 people in nine southern states
since February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
