<HEADLINE> Chinese Girl Wins Violin Competition in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Wang Zhijiong, a 14-year-old
Chinese violinist, has won first prize in the junior category of
1998 Yehudi Menuhin Young Violinists International Competition in
Boulogne-sur-Mer, Calais, France.
</P>
<P>
Wang, a student at the elementary school of Shanghai Music
Conservatory, came to the top among 24 competitors aged below 16
from 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
The Yehudi Menuhin Young Violinists International Competition,
which was created in 1983 by Jewish musician Menuhin, is held
every two years.
</P>
<P>
The jury of this year's competition is headed by Erich
Gruenber, a professor of the Royal Academy of Music of London, and
included Menuhin himself and French violinist Augustin Dumay.
</P>
<P>
The final competition of the senior category, joined by 20
violinists aged from 16 to 22, will be held Friday evening.
</P>
