<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WIPO Official Praises China's IPR Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China has achieved "tremendous
progress" in protecting the intellectual property rights over the
past two decades, said Francois Curchod, director-general of the
World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) today.
</P>
<P>
"China has made tremendous progress since taking steps to open
to foreign countries," said Curchod. "China has also promulgated a
number of laws, including the Trademark Law and Intellectual Property
Rights Law.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua today, Curchod said, "We
are highly impressed with the fact that China has developed a very
good legislative system in IPR protection."
</P>
<P>
"The WIPO is very happy about China's contributions and
development. And China's intellectual property system was
nonexistent 20 years ago," said Curchod.
</P>
<P>
The nation has adopted trademark, patent and copy rights laws
as well as regulations on the protection of computer software and
the law against unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
Curchod expressed appreciation to the Chinese government's
efforts in enhancing the awareness of the general public on
intellectual property rights protection. He noted that "related
efforts are extremely difficult in a country as large as China."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "the recent establishment of the China
Intellectual Property Training Center represents another big step
forward."
</P>
<P>
The center will provide intellectual property rights training
for senior professionals. Furthermore, the center, as an important
base in both the country and the Asia-Pacific Region, will
collect the most elite academic works in the field.
</P>
<P>
"China has promoted a greater awareness of intellectual
property, and the WIPO intends to continue and enhance close
cooperation with the nation," said Curchod.
</P>
<P>
"China should tell the WIPO what it expects and we will
certainly respond positively to related requests."
</P>
<P>
The WIPO was founded in 1967 as part of an endeavor to enhance
IPR protection throughout the world. China joined the organization
and has since signed nine international cooperation treaties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
