<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Aims to Wipe out Polio By 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Deputy Minister of Health
Teresa Cohen said Friday that the government has planned to
inoculate three million children under five years old against
polio starting from August or September.
</P>
<P>
Three million children under age of five years in 164 towns
and cities of 18 provinces will be vaccinated in 1998, Cohen
announced here at a meeting reviewing the work in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
Angola aims to wipe out the infantile polio by the year of
2000, she said, adding that about 2.8 million and 2.6 million
children received vaccination in 1996 and 1997 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said that with the support of the international
organizations and enterprises based in Angola, her government is
determinated to greatly reduce the number of the polio cases, but
there are still difficulties for the southern African country to
meet the target set by the World Health Organization of wiping
out polio before 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, she said, in 80 percent of the areas formerly
controlled by the National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, local governments have been reestablished, making
vaccination much easier.
</P>
<P>
Besides strongly pushing for vaccination, Cohen stressed the
need for health institutions to strengthen monitoring of the
disease.
</P>
<P>
But she said since there is no specialistic laboratory in
Angola, the samples have to be sent to South Africa for analysis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gambill, Black Fight Into Japan Open Semis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Jan-Michael Gambill of United
States and Byron Black remained unbeaten in the Japan Open tennis
tournament after they defeated their quarter-finals opponents here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 11th seed Gambill, ranked 81st in the world, upset the
third seed Tim Henman, ranked 15th, 6-3, 4-6, 6-3 with his
powerful double-fisted ground strokes, while Black, seeded 10th,
fought off a hard-hitting Hendrik Dreekmann of Germany, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Patrick Rafter of Australia and second Michael Chang
of the United States have fallen out in earlier round.
</P>
<P>
Gambill will face 16th seed Andrei Pavel of Romania, who beat
American qualifier David Dilucia 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) in Saturday's
semifinal, while Black set up a clash with 12th seed Daniel Vacek
of the Czech Republic, the winner over David Prinosil of Germany
6-4, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
On the women's side, defending champion Ai Sugiyama came back
from one set down to keep the local hopes alive after she beat
American Erika De Lone 4-6, 6-1, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Sugiyama's semi-final opponent will be Wang Shi-ting of Chinese
Taipei, a 4-6, 6-4, 6-1 winner over 1991 Japan Open champion Lori
McNeil of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The other match will be played between the 1995 Japan Open
winner and three-time runner-up, Amy Frazier, and fellow American
Corina Morariu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
