<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of Key Railway Begins in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The construction of a multi-track
railway linking Zhuzhou City, the industrial center of central
China's Hunan Province, and Liupanshui, the major coal production
base in south China, commenced today.
</P>
<P>
The railway will stretch 1,141.75 km, with plans calling for
the 617-km section in southwest China's Guizhou Province to be
completed within five years at an estimated cost of 17.1 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the railway will "benefit the exploitation of
abundant resources in the region," according to Teng Yuhe,
director of the Railway Bureau in Chengdu, capital of southwest
China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The central government will allocate half of the total
investment, with the remainder coming from bank loans, said Teng.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Railways recently announced that China will
invest 250 billion yuan in railway construction over the next five
years. Experts say the central government's efforts will ensure
sustained economic growth based on expanded infrastructure
construction.
</P>
<P>
The massive project will place priority on west China,
particularly southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Railways Sun Yongfu said that southwest China
remains as the bottleneck of the nation's railway network, a fact
which has hampered rapid economic growth in the region.
</P>
<P>
Plans for the next five years call for investments of over 68
billion yuan to either construct or improve some 20 medium- to
large-sized railway projects in southwest China, or some 31
percent of the total investment in the national railway
construction.
</P>
<P>
Completion of related projects will form railway network in
southwest China and will in turn reduce current stress on the
regional network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
