<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imperial City Walls Unearthed in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Two sections of the ancient
Imperial City Wall dating back over 600 years to the Ming Dynasty
(1368-1644) were recently discovered in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The wall sections, which are separated by some 700 meters, were
discovered during ongoing construction work on Ping'an Avenue near
the Imperial Gardens in the Dongcheng District.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists and historians have also unearthed a 50-meter
section of the wall's foundation which was constructed with four
layers of ancient bricks.
</P>
<P>
Archeologist Su Tianjun pointed out that four separate walls
formed concentric squares surrounding the imperial capital of the
Ming Dynasty. The recently discovered sections were part of
nine-km northern side of the second wall which surrounded the
famous Forbidden City, or palace complex for the imperial family.
</P>
<P>
The area between the second wall and Forbidden City was
occupied by imperial offices for military departments and dynastic
organizations, said Sun, adding that residents living outside of
the second wall were prohibited from entering the office compound.
</P>
<P>
The discovery has further verified the location of the city's
outer walls and will provide clues for further studies of the
structure and architectural designing of the imperial city, said
Sun.
</P>
<P>
"Scholars are currently examining wall bricks bearing the
construction date and names of craftsmen to prove the exact age of
the city walls," according to Sun.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Meets High-tech Scholars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met today
with scholars from China's inland areas and the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) attending a high-tech symposium in
the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee member of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central
Committee, discussed the current economic situations in inland
areas and Hong Kong, as well as the financial crisis in Southeast
Asia and the development of high technology.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that scholars from the two sides will
strengthen cooperation and score major achievements in the realm
of high technology.
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium, which ended today, was jointly sponsored
by the Chinese Academy of Engineering and the Hong Kong Academy of
Engineering Sciences. The event attracted more than 200
scientists, businessmen and government officials.
</P>
<P>
Participants shared the view that it is the best option for
the two sides to establish complementary cooperation in high-tech
development on the basis of their unique advantages.
</P>
<P>
Priorities for cooperation should center on new technology
related to information, bio-engineering and new materials,
according to the participants.
</P>
<P>
The sponsors have also decided to hold the next high-tech
symposium in Hong Kong in the year 2000, and have pledged to
establish regular contacts to strengthen exchanges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
