<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reunified Cyprus Will Be There, Says President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides Friday expressed his confidence in seeing a reunification
of Cyprus and the ensuing resurrection in the east Mediterranean
island.
</P>
<P>
"As long as we have what it takes to achieve our objective, we
are sure that at the end of the day justice awaits us," the
president said in his Easter message.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the island's accession negotiations with the
European Union (EU), which began last month, "gives a fresh
impetus to our hopes and strengthens our faith in our
resurrection."
</P>
<P>
The president said that "Cyprus has been suffering for the past
24 years as a direct result of the Turkish invasion and
continuing occupation of part of its territory."
</P>
<P>
Clerides expressed the hope that "next year we shall celebrate
Easter in a united, peaceful and happy Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-led international community has been trying for
decades to reunite the divided island as a bizonal, bicommunal
federation through peace talks, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
