<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Million Female Condoms Sold in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Four million female condoms have
been sold in the developing world in the first quarter of 1998,
thanks to a United Nations initiative to encourage their use.
</P>
<P>
Countries with substantial sales this year have been South
Africa, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe, the Joint United Nations
Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The female condom, made of polyurethane, is a sheath that a
woman inserts into her vagina, which offers a new barrier method
of protection to couples.
</P>
<P>
The condom, while protecting against sexually transmitted
diseases (STDs), also acts as a contraceptive.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement between UNAIDS and the Female Health
Company, of the United States, the sole manufacturer of the female
condom, it is priced at 25 percent lower than in the developed
world.
</P>
<P>
The growing interest in the female condom has prompted the
UNAIDS, in collaboration with the World Health Organization and
other partners, to organize a meeting in Pretoria, South Africa,
on April 20-22, to discuss ways of encouraging greater use in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Adopts High-Tech Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior officer with the
Headquarters of the General Staff of the People's Liberation Army
(PLA) said here today that the focus of military training has
turned to the acquisition of knowledge and skills in the realm of
high technology.
</P>
<P>
The new direction represents an important move to improve the
quality of the army and will promote military modernization,
according to the officer in charge of military training.
</P>
<P>
He said that military training has changed over the decades
with significant growth from low to high standards and from the
former focus on a single branch of the army to the integration of
various branches.
</P>
<P>
Military training in the early days of the People's Republic of
China focused on cultivating sharpshooters and developing special
skills.
</P>
<P>
Decrees, regulations and teaching materials compiled and issued
during the 1960s centered on standardizing military training.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese army began placing priority on the combination of
various branches of the armed forces in the 1980s in order to
enhance the command capabilities of officers and the coordinated
combat capability of soldiers.
</P>
<P>
At present military training focuses on ensuring that both
officers and men grasp an understanding of high technology in
accordance with the prevailing situation, according to the officer.
</P>
<P>
He said the three-year program introduced in 1997 urged
military officers to gain a wide understanding of high
technology.  
</P>
