<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: Highest Rate of Deaths from Firearms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States has the
highest rate of peacetime deaths from firearms in the world,
according to a new survey.
</P>
<P>
Firearm-related deaths numbered 14.24 per 100,000, said the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP) in a survey of
36 countries published Thursday in the International Journal of
Epidemiology.
</P>
<P>
Brazil had the second-highest firearm death rate, with 12.95
deaths per 100,000 population, followed by Mexico and Estonia,
which also had rates above 12 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
Japan had the lowest rate, with 0.05 deaths per 100,000
population.
</P>
<P>
The countries in the survey reported a total of 88,649 firearm
deaths during the one-year survey period. In 1993, firearms were
involved in the deaths of 39,395 people in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the researchers said firearm mortality rates were five
to six times higher in the United States, Canada, Mexico, Brazil
and Argentina, than in European and Oceanian nations.
</P>
<P>
The United States also had the highest proportion of
firearm-related suicides and the third-highest rate of accidental
firearm deaths.
</P>
<P>
Firearms were also involved in 71 percent of murders in the
United States, the third-highest rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Washington Insist on Unconditional Dialogue in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott have reasserted
a demand for unconditional dialogue between Belgrade and
Kosovo-Albanian leaders with the participation of an international
mediator, the German foreign ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting in Bonn Friday, Kinkel and Talbott claimed
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had so far failed to
meet the demands made by the six-nation Contact Group at its last
meeting on March 25 in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the Contact Group, consisting of Britain,
France, Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States, would move
to impose new punitive measures on Belgrade if Milosevic still
refused to put forward a trustworthy offer for dialogue, the
foreign ministry added.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav parliament, wary of foreign intervention in the
Kosovo conflict, decided earlier to hold a referendum on whether
to involve a third party in a political dialogue over the future
status of Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
