<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's SPD Crowns Schroeder as Chancellor Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) has formally elected Gerhard Schroeder as
its candidate to challenge Chancellor Helmut Kohl in the national
elections in September.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was confirmed by an overwhelming majority of 93
percent of the vote at a special SPD party congress in the eastern
German city of Leipzig on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, the 54-year-old premier of the western German Lower
Saxony state, has emerged as the greatest hope for the leftist
SPD, which has been in opposition for 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Declaring "the Kohl era is over," Schroeder told the 515
delegates at the congress that the SPD was now ready to take over
the German leadership to face challenges in a new century.
</P>
<P>
He pledged to make job creation the top priority of a SPD-led
government and to take a pragmatic approach to resolve the
problems facing Germany.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has been widely seen as the most dangerous SPD
challenger to Kohl since the 1980s because he has more chance of
winning vital centrist votes, which are also much needed by Kohl's
center-right ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
He has also been leading Kohl in popularity in almost all
opinion polls over the past year.
</P>
<P>
As an active proponent of high-technology investments and a
former board member of Germany's largest carmaker Volkswagen AG,
Schroeder often says that he understands the challenges faced by
German businesses in global markets and pledges to undertake
reforms to improve Germany's competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
And as one of the five children raised by a war widow who
earned a living as a cleaning lady, Schroeder also said he wanted
to promote social justice at a time when Germany faces a post-war
record unemployment rate of about 4.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
With Schroeder as the SPD candidate for chancellor, German
commentators are now predicting a much harder re-election battle
for Kohl who is already the longest-serving European political
leader.
</P>
<P>
The national elections are scheduled to be held on September
27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
