<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Deport Japanese Terrorist Suspect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus Police Friday decided to
deport a Japanese terrorist suspect, who was allegedly involved in
the 1995 deadly gas attack upon Tokyo subways, Cyprus News Agency
(CNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Toshiyasu Ouchi, a leading member of the Japanese doomsday
cult, arrived here from Russia last month and was detained
earlier Friday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Ouchi was placed on the wanted list in Japan on April 2 for
connection with the nerve gas attack which left 12 people dead and
thousands injured.
</P>
<P>
He is also suspected of involvement in the murder of a fellow
cult member, 21-year-old Shuji Taguchi, who tried to escape from
the sect's commune at the foot of Mount Fuji in 1989.
</P>
<P>
CNA quoted a Police spokesman as saying that Ouchi was issued
with two warrants, declaring him a persona non-grata and ordering
him to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
The warrants also revoke his temporary permit of stay in
Cyprus, which is due to expire on May 6, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Ouchi was spotted at a local hotel early Friday morning by
police officers who took him to the police station.
</P>
<P>
A woman, who was with the suspect, is also expected to be
deported.
</P>
<P>
Police has said that there is no extradition treaty between
Cyprus and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
