-- President Clinton acknowledged in Chile that he had not
convinced a majority in the Congress of the benefits of free trade
throughout the hemisphere. But he vowed to press for approval of a
free trade pact and a fast track authority.
</P>
<P>
-- A report said that the level of violence on television has
remained about the same for three years, but the number of violent
programs appearing in prime time has increased, on both broadcast
and cable networks.
</P>
<P>
-- Declaring that there was no end in sight to his probe of the
president, the Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr
announced Thursday that he would give up high-level positions at a
university with close ties to a millionaire who has financed
attacks on the president.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Federal regulators Thursday proposed overhauling the wiring
of the most popular passenger jet in the world, the Boeing 737,
because information gleaned from the Crash of TWA Flight 800 has
raised doubts about the safety of its fuel-monitoring system.
</P>
<P>
-- The Republican National Committee has filed a suit against
the Federal Election Commission, arguing that it should be allowed
to pay for "issue advertising" entirely with "soft money," the
unlimited contributions parties raise from wealthy individuals,
corporations and labor unions.
</P>
<P>
-- A teary Paula Jones, barely able to compose herself,
announced Thursday that she will appeal a federal judge's ruling
that her sexual harassment case against President Clinton has no
merit.
</P>
