<HEADLINE> African Renaissance Offers Opportunities to Asia: Mbeki </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting South African
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki said here Friday that Asians and Africans
must reach across the great geographical divide, to build a
partnership of mutual respect and a mutually beneficial
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a luncheon hosted by the Hong Kong Center of the
Asian Society and the South African Business Forum in Hong Kong,
Mbeki, who is on a two-day visit to Hong Kong, said that he
believed that Africa's renewal through its native-born Renaissance
presents an opportunity to Asia to benefit from Africa's enormous
economic potential.
</P>
<P>
"The Africa of today is an Africa of hope, a continent that has
resumed its journey out of the period of despair," said Mbeki in
his speech titled "African Renaissance -- Opportunities and
Challenges for Asia."
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said that South Africa belongs to the regional
inter-state organization, the Southern African Development
Community, whose combined population is 140 million people.
</P>
<P>
The member countries of the SADC are involved in negotiations
to transform the sub-continent into a free trade area which would
further enhance the attractiveness of the countries of the region
as an investment destination and a base from which to reach into
the larger African market, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is an important center of the world economy, Mbeki
said. "We are greatly encouraged by the fact that the Hong Kong
Trade Development Council opened an office in South Africa as well
as the existence in Hong Kong of the South African Business
Forum," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"As the government of South Africa, we are keenly interested to
cooperate with these bodies to look for and exploit all ways and
means by which we can increase our economic cooperation," Mbeki
added.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki arrived in Hong Kong on Thursday from Seoul following his
visit to Japan and China's inland areas. He is traveling with his
wife and a party of 14 senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Thursday evening, Mbeki attended a dinner hosted by Tung Chee
Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki called on the HKSAR Financial Secretary Donald Tsang
Friday morning. He will depart Hong Kong for Johannesburg Friday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
