<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Government Quits Old Way of Pricing Cotton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's longtime official pricing
system on cotton has been abolished as the government has decided
to adopt an indirect control over the field.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, the government will only issue directive
prices for cotton and the market will play a bigger role in
pricing.
</P>
<P>
This reform has been undertaken because of difficulties in the
domestic cotton market, which became a buyer's market in recent
years, according to officials from the State Development and
Planning commission.
</P>
<P>
The officials disclosed that the government purchase prices for
cotton will also be lowered to cool down the enthusiasm of local
cotton growers.
</P>
<P>
The current government-set cotton prices reportedly are much
higher than those of imported cotton, while grain prices in the
local market have been plummeting.
</P>
<P>
As a result, local farmers have found it more profitable to
grow cotton than grain, which has led to a surplus cotton supply.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, the country produced 4.3 billion
kilograms (kg) of cotton in 1997, 100 million kg more than the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The price cut is expected to affect local cotton growers, but
it will benefit them in the long term, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Officials expressed their hope that the pricing reform will
reinvigorate the country's lingering cotton market and boost
exports. It will not affect the country's cotton production as a
whole, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Afflicts Pearl River Mouth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
province is suffering its most serious red tide in history, with
150 tons of fish killed in Shenzhen and 50 tons in Zhuhai, local
government officials revealed today.
</P>
<P>
The economic loss to Shenzhen, a special economic zone
neighboring Hong Kong, is estimated at 20 million yuan (2.4
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Red tides, which occur frequently in the sea near the Pearl
River estuary, is caused by the explosive breeding of seaweed and
other planktons which cover the surface of the ocean and stop
oxygen in the air from going into the sea water.
</P>
<P>
Fish suffocate because of an oxygen shortage or from seaweed
clogging their gills.
</P>
<P>
Experts in the Guangdong Provincial Department of Ocean and
Aquatic Products say the red tide normally occurs in May
and June. This year, it quickly spread to a large sea area and
lasted longer than previous years, they said. Sea areas near
Shenzhen, Zhuhai and Hong Kong are all seriously affected by the
red tide.
</P>
<P>
Fishermen are now fighting against the disaster day and night,
trying to save fish by such measures as adding oxygen.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has also sent experts to the
disaster-hit areas to monitor changes of the red tide and try to
resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Signs of a decrease in the red tide in the Pearl River
estuary have begun to appear.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0125 </DOCNO>
