<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Auto Industry Takes Downward Turn in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The output and sales of China's
automobiles dropped slightly in the first quarter of this year
compared to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the State Bureau of
Machinery Industry, Chinese manufacturers turned out 364,700
automobiles from January through March, 2.72 percent down from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In this period, 355,500 automobiles were sold, a decrease of
1.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the auto industry said that the slump was due to a
usually sluggish season combined with a sharp decrease in orders
from governments.
</P>
<P>
Most institutions of the central government have canceled or
halted plans to buy business cars, because of the on-going
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
However, industrial analysts said that the trend of China's
auto market remained optimistic this year. They said that, though
output and sales were sharply down in January, they began to pick
up in February and reached the highest levels this year in
March. Production and sales of automobiles in March stood at
155,000 and 157,000, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Mini passenger cars for household use defied the downward trend
of the auto industry by respectively registering 17-percent and
3.43-percent increases in sales and output over the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 62,000 mini-cars were sold while 57,800 were
produced in the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Auto experts said that this is another indication that growing
demand for private cars has become a stable driving force of the
industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
