<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Renominates Kiriyenko as Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Friday officially renominated Sergei Kiriyenko as his candidate
for prime minister for a third round vote, shortly after his young
protege was rejected by the State Duma (the lower house of
parliament) for the second time.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, plucked by Yeltsin from relative obscurity last
month to form a new government, mustered just 115 votes in the
450-seat State Duma, with 271 deputies voting against. Eleven
deputies abstained.
</P>
<P>
He needed 226 votes in the 450-seat chamber to secure his
confirmation.
</P>
<P>
Kremlin officials said Yeltsin had prepared the necessary
papers to resubmit Kiriyenko's nomination for a decisive third
round next week.
</P>
<P>
If the Duma rejects Yeltsin's choice as premier three times,
the president can dissolve the Duma and call early elections.
</P>
<P>
Deputies rejected Kiriyenko's candidacy in the first attempt on
April 10. He gained 143 of the 226 votes needed.
</P>
<P>
The Russian president abruptly dismissed veteran Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin and the entire government on March 23, and
formally named Kiriyenko as his choice for prime minister on March
27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
