<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korea Talks Expected To End Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) - The first inter-Korean high-level
contact will reopen and conclude here Saturday, as the North has
indicated it would no longer participate even if there is no
progress after seven days of talks.
</P>
<P>
"Tomorrow would be the last day we're at the Beijing talks,
even if both sides cannot reach agreement," said Chun Kum Chul,
chief delegate of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
There was no obvious progress in the talks, he said, adding the
South should not link an economic and humanitarian issue, the
fertilizer aid, to a political one, the reunion of separated
families.
</P>
<P>
The fertilizer aid is an urgent issue, as the spring planting
period is approaching and the DPRK has suffered three years of
floods and drought, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chun said the reunion issue can be discussed later at Red Cross
talks between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning China's recent aid of 100,000 tons of grain and
20,000 tons of chemical fertilizer to the DPRK, he said China has
given all this without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Jeong Se Hyun, leader of the Republic of Korea (ROK)
delegation, reiterated at a news briefing this afternoon his
position that the North should agree to a timetable to help
reunite separated families in return for fertilizer aid from the
South.
</P>
<P>
The 200,000 tons of fertilizer that the ROK offers can be
delivered this year, but the fertilizer aid and reunion issues
must be discussed simultaneously at the current talks, he
stressed, adding what matters most is that the substance of the
matter be dealt with on a basis of reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
Jeong said he hoped for a change in the North's position, and
the North could change its stance at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
The North-South talks on the reunion issue started in 1971 and
continued until 1973 with some progress, but eventually came to
nothing because of the lack of a timetable, according to Jeong.
</P>
<P>
The talks will reopen at 10 a.m. Saturday at the hotel where
the ROK delegation is staying, followed by a news briefing by the
ROK side.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
