<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Share prices fluctuated within
a narrow range on the Singapore market while the benchmark Straits
Times Industrials Index (STII) ended at the starting level of
1,515.15 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that they could see only modest near-term gains
given the economic uncertainties clouding Asia, as stock prices
closed absolutely flat. Lingering fears included the poor Japanese
economy and Malaysia's corporate developments, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The index was underpinned by gains in SPH (Singapore Press
Holdings) ahead of its results for the six months ended February
1998 after the market closes on Friday, they said.
</P>
<P>
Advances overtook declines by 205 to 136, while 370 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Easyknit was the most actively traded counter as it registered
a turnover of 11.47 million units. It was followed by Rekapac
which had 8.98 million shares traded. MBf Capital was next with
7.53 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign Right100 led the
gainers of the day as it rose by 33 cents to finish at 2.32
Singapore dollars. SPH (Singapore Press Holdings) increased by 30
cents to end at 16.7 Singapore dollars. BATS was up by 26 cents to
close at 4.96 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Network was the biggest loser as it declined
by 52 cents to end at 0.45 Singapore dollar. RothmansI fell by 35
cents to close at 7.4 Singapore dollars, while Thai Prime lost 25
cents to finish at 4.8 U.S. dollars. 
