<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs to Sign Anti-Terrorism Accord in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Arab ministers of interior and
justice will sign an Arab agreement on combating terrorism in the
Egyptian capital on April 22, Egypt's Middle East News Agency
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is considered a basic and prominent step taken by
the Arab countries to face up to the challenge of terrorist crimes.
</P>
<P>
It renounces all forms of violence and terrorism and bases its
clauses on the principles of Islam and international law,
according to Egyptian Minister of Justice Farouk Seik el-Nasr.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will be signed at a meeting of Arab interior and
justice ministers to be inaugurated on Wednesday by Arab League
Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid and chaired by Saudi Interior
Minister Prince Nayef Bin Abdel-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first of its kind within the framework of
joint Arab action, is expected to be attended by 30 Arab interior
and justice ministers.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be held two days following the meetings of the
Executive Bureau of the Arab Justice Ministers Council on Monday
at the Arab League headquarters, to be attended by the ministers
of justice of Egypt, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Morocco and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Once the agreement is endorsed, a security source in the
Egyptian Ministry of Interior said, it will play a key role in
helping Arab security bodies fight and constrict the phenomenon of
terrorism in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Egypt itself has been fighting a violent campaign launched by
militant Muslims since 1992 with an aim to overthrow the secular
social system and install a strict Islamic rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
