<HEADLINE> U.S. Considers Pakistan Strategic Ally: Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government considers
Pakistan a strategic friend and ally with which it wants to build
an all-embracing relationship, visiting U.S. Ambassador to the
United Nations Bill Richardson said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The relationship will help promote peace in the region and the
economic development in Pakistan, said Richardson during a meeting
with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
It was the second meeting between the two since Richardson
arrived here Wednesday from New Delhi on a two-day official visit
to Pakistan. They held a meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Richardson, who is visiting the region as a special envoy of
U.S. President Bill Clinton, also said that the United States
greatly valued the positive role that Pakistan was playing in the
region and wanted to work closely together with Islamabad for the
promotion of peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was aware of the issue relating to peace, security and
non-proliferation in the region and was, therefore, advocating to
both India and Pakistan to engage themselves in a comprehensive
dialogue to resolve all their problems, including the issue of
Jammu and Kashmir, Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Sharif emphasized the importance of the U.S.
active efforts for promoting peace and stability in Afghanistan as
well as the whole region.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two men also exchanged views with
regard to the substantive aspects of Clinton's forthcoming visit
to Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
