<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Lower Marginally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
closed marginally down on Friday, but off its lows in lacklustre
trade, with investors taking profits and choosing the sidelines
ahead of Wall Street's opening on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Falls on northern hemisphere bourses overnight and softer
commodity prices dragged domestic stocks down in the morning
session and kept the trading in the afternoon session in negative
territory.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed down 13.9 points, or 0.48
percent, at 2867.5 after trading between 2881.4 and 2858.6.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index was up 0.3 of a point at 1222.3 and the
all industrials index was down 30.1 points at 4927.7.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 279.17 million shares exchanged, valued
at 509.1 million U.S. dollars. Falls outnumbered rises by 653 to
435 respectively, with 454 stocks remaining steady.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank lost 13 cents to 22.97 Australian
dollars, Commonwealth Bank of Australia dropped 23 cents to 19.22
Australian dollars, while Westpac Banking Corp gained 7.7 cents to
11.12 Australian dollars and ANZ Banking Group gained 1.7 cents to
11.759 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Market heavyweight News Corp kept the sharemarket from further
losses, with its two classes of shares gaining ground.
</P>
<P>
Its ordinary shares were up 24 cents, or 2.22 percent, at 11.06
Australian dollars and its preferred shares were also up 24 cents,
or 2.56 percent, at 9.60 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Resources major BHP fell 13.9 cents to 15.52 Australian dollars
after the copper price fell overnight.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto gained 53 cents, or 2.55 percent, to
21.28 Australian dollars after a London brokerage house Dresdner
Kleinwort Benson said the Anglo-Australian listed miner's stock
price was undervalued.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 2.9 points higher, or 0.22 percent, at
1306.4.
</P>
<P>
Sydney trading in gold bullion closed 1.95 U.S. dollars higher
at 308.45 U.S. dollars an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
