<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Government to Hand Over Control of Internet: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
will hand over control of the Internet to an independent global
board, a senior adviser to U.S. President Bill Clinton said here
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ira Magaziner, President Clinton's information technology
policy adviser, said one reason for U.S. distancing itself from
the Internet was to reduce the government's legal liability for
companies that operated from the Internet, originally set up by
the U.S. Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
"What we are looking to do is to turn over all the authorities
we have to a neutral, private, non-profit organization that would
have a fully international board of directors which would be
constructed in a way so that it could withstand legal challenges
and not have to depend on the authority of the U.S. government or
any other government," the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
Magaziner said the government wanted the new entity in place by
mid-year and expected it would be based in the U.S. at first.
</P>
<P>
The new entity's functions included allocating blocks of
numbers (currently done by the U.S.'s Internet Assigned Numbers
Authority), protocol directives, and allocating domain names,
those suffixes on Internet addresses such as .com, .org and .net.
said Magaziner, who is in Australia for the nation's first
electronic commerce meeting which ended on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ownership of the .com, .org and .net databases would be handed
over to the new organization, which would set policy for these and
new domain names, he said.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said whether the new entity, envisaged by the United
States, will be accepted by other countries, particularly the
European Union, remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department published a program last February
aiming to transfer the management of the Internet to a private
business.
</P>
<P>
The program was later opposed by the European Union and
Australia, arguing the program would strengthen U.S.'s control
over the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
