<HEADLINE> Chinese Software Industry Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's software industry has
entered a period of rapid growth, dominating many areas on the
domestic market and follow global trends, according to Shen Shibo,
with the China Software Industry Association (CSIA).
</P>
<P>
Shen told Xinhua that the industry has developed software to
meet the special needs of the Chinese customers. CSIA and its
2,000 members chooses outstanding Chinese software every year, and
selected 59 out of more than 200 entries this year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that convenience and cost are the reasons they are
popular in China. Yongyou accounting management software, for
example, is regarded by Chinese users as one of top ten software
items. And, a regional computer banking system developed by
Beijing University has greatly improved banking services in
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of the Information Industry official says that
China's software industry took only ten years to go from
practically nowhere to developing all kinds of software. The
industry's strategy, he said, is to develop specialized software
by using mature and popular software systems of other countries.
</P>
<P>
Chinese information technology giants like Stone and Hope have
already allocated funds for developing software that can be used
with Windows and Unix, Shen said, and this type of software
suggests a huge Chinese software market.
</P>
<P>
China's software has had double-digit growth over the past few
years. In 1997, total software sales were 11.2 billion yuan (1.4
billion US dollars), more than 20 percent more than in
1996. Chinese software sales totaled 150 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Software for the insurance business, to take another example,
is relatively scarce, Shen says, meaning that software has great
potential in this area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
