<HEADLINE> China, Canada Sign Three Cooperative Memos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China and Canada here today signed
memorandums of understanding (MOU) on three cooperative
projects that will help China reduce poverty in rural areas, make
women aware of their rights and train telecommunications engineers.
</P>
<P>
The three projects will involve investments from both sides
totaling more than 20 million Canadian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi
Guangsheng and visiting Canadian Minister for International
Cooperation Diane Marleau signed the three MOUs after a meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Shi said there have been many cooperative
projects between China and Canada on poverty relief, environmental
protection and education.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 of the total 70 strong Sino-Canadian cooperative
projects have been completed with good results, said Shi, adding
that the Chinese government and people appreciate the support and
assistance from the Canadian government and people.
</P>
<P>
Shi said China hopes to further strengthen bilateral
cooperation in environmental protection, health care for women and
children, and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
Marleau said there is great potential for bilateral cooperation
in environmental protection, and Canada is willing to share its
experience with China in management training.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her hope that Sino-Canadian cooperation will be
strengthened on the basis of those successful projects.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving in Beijing, Marleau visited Yunnan Province and
Shanghai.  
</P>
