<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Loses Five Billion Dollars to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria loses about five billion
U.S. Dollars annualy, an equivalent of the country's annual
budget, to environmental degradation, according to a World Bank
study.
</P>
<P>
The content of the study, "Towards the Preparation of Nigerian
Environmental Action Plan", was disclosed by R.O. Adewole,
director general of the Federal Environmental Protection Agency,
at a recent workshop held in the oil-producing city of Port
Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
Adewole reminded the participants that besides the global
environmental issues, such as drought and desertification,
climate change, ozone layer depletion and toxic waste dumping,
Nigeria has many of its own environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
Such problems, he said, include erosion, flooding, oil spills,
mining waste, gas flare, effluent discharges and municipal waste.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government has realized the problems and is
taking measures to reverse the situation.
</P>
<P>
The efforts, he said, include evolving new environmental
policies, building legal and institutional frameworks, capacity
building and co-operation with international organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
