<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Assets Classification Key to China's Financial Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Classification of credit assets
in line with international practice is the key to China's
financial reform and risk prevention this year, said Dai
Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China (PBOC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking to directors of national PBOC branches at a recent
meeting, Dai said it is an urgent task for the financial sector to
prevent risks.
</P>
<P>
Although China has a fairly good macro-economic situation and
has avoided the direct impact of the Southeast Asian financial
crisis, latent risks in the financial sector should be clearly
noticed, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that the classification of credit assets will not only
significantly promote commercial banks' management, but will also
help enhance the central bank's supervision level and the
professional quality of banking staff members.
</P>
<P>
He added that the classification will make clear the degree of
risk and actual losses of various credit assets so as to create an
appropriate environment for developing a new loan-classification
system.
</P>
<P>
He said the money supply in the first quarter of this year is
basically suited to the economic growth, but problems still exist
in both economic development and money supply and demand. Efforts
should be made to readjust credit structure in line with the
state's industrial policies and improve financial services.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, foreign exchange supervision should be
further reinforced so as to maintain the balance of international
payments and protect the stability of the exchange rate of China's
currency, the Renminbi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
