<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Companies' Cash-Flow Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of Finance
today issued a new accounting norm, a cash-flow report, to
standardize enterprises' cash management.
</P>
<P>
The ministry demanded that all companies in the country must
implement this report in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the ministry said that, with the transition of
enterprises' operating mechanisms, cash flow has been playing an
increasingly important role in the operation and management of
companies. The new norm is designed to meet the demand of
enterprises and tally with international accounting standards.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the cash-flow report will become one of the
major public reports of enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The cash-flow report enables enterprises to capture cash-flow
information and maximize the working efficiency of enterprise
funds, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, cash-flow information is an important basis for
related government departments, especially the exchange market
supervision department, to supervise enterprises and prevent
latent risks.
</P>
<P>
A cash-flow report can also allow investors and creditors to
know how cash is used by the company and the enterprise's
capability for future cash return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
