<HEADLINE> More Foreign Insurance Companies Allowed to Do Business in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
announced today that three more foreign insurance companies have
been ratified to do business in China.
</P>
<P>
-- The British Royal Sun Alliance Insurance Group has been
approved to set up a branch in Shanghai to operate in the asset
insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian Colonial Mutual Group has been allowed to set
up a Sino-foreign joint venture in Shanghai for life insurance.
</P>
<P>
-- The French AXA-UAP Insurance Group also has been given the
green light to set up a life insurance joint venture in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the PBOC said that the latest move shows that
the Southeast Asian financial crisis has not affected China's
policy of continuing to open up its insurance market.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, China has opened the insurance market of Shanghai
and Guangzhou to foreign companies. So far, foreign insurance
companies -- mainly from the United States, Japan, Switzerland and
Canada -- have established seven offices in the two cities, the
spokesman added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
