<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Opposes Dramatizing Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said on Friday that he is opposed to dramatizing the cabinet
crisis and all government agencies should work in accordance with
the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
"The dismissal of the government is a rare event for our
country, but it happened within the framework of law, as provided
by the constitution," said Yeltsin in his regular radio address,
who sacked former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and the whole
government on March 23.
</P>
<P>
Although Yeltsin admitted that Russia was in a state of
"political crisis", he refused to say that it was a disaster. "All
the ministries and government institutions are working, and a
normal political process is underway," Yeltsin added.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, the lower house of parliament, is expected to
vote later on Friday for the second time on Yeltsin's prime
minister nominee Sergei Kiriyenko, who used to be the fuel
minister and appointed by the president as acting premier in March.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko did not pass the first round of vote in the Duma on
April 10.
</P>
<P>
But after that, Yeltsin immediately nominated Kiriyenko again
for the premiership.
</P>
<P>
Under Russia's constitution, Yeltsin has the right to dissolve
the Duma if it fails to pass the three nominations he has raised
for the premiership.
</P>
<P>
Some Duma deputies have suggested that the constitution be
changed to make the chairman of the parliament's upper house,
rather than the prime minister, the number two in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, Yeltsin expressed his opposition to constitutional
amendment, saying that "it is very dangerous to alter the
constitution in the middle of reforms, because it is the basis of
the country's stability."
</P>
<P>
It is because of the guarantee of the constitution that Russia
has been away from upheavals and coups in recent years, Yeltsin
added.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who is due to leave for Japan just hours after the
second vote on his nominee Sergei Kiriyenko in the Duma, said that
the visit was very important and he saw "no grounds to postpone the
visit." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
