<HEADLINE> Inter-governmental Meeting Held for Tumen River Area Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- An inter-governmental meeting
which ended here today mapped out a yearly plan on the development
of the Tumen River Area, a border region linking China with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), Mongolia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, sponsored by the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP), brought together National Team
Coordinators from member countries such as China, DPRK, Mongolia,
Republic of Korea (ROK) and the Russian Federation.
</P>
<P>
According to a UNDP press release, the meeting was held in
preparation for the Inter-governmental Meeting of Vice-Ministers
scheduled for October in Ulan Bator, capital of Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
The Tumen Program, initiated in 1991, aims to promote regional
economic cooperation in northeast China, particularly in the Tumen
River Economic Development Area.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the UNDP's budget for the program is
3.2 million U.S. dollars for the 1997-99 period. Other donor
assistance for related projects in the Tumen Region amounts to 10
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the member states endorsed a blueprint for
1998, which included reducing impediments to cross-border people
and goods, opening of inter-state railways and checkpoints,
improving port facilities, as well as environmental issues of
concern to all members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
