<HEADLINE> China's Largest Insurer Posts 32.5 Percent Premium Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's largest insurance company
reported stable business in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The People's Insurance Company of China (PICC) Group received
22.54 billion yuan in premiums in the first three months of this
year, up 32.5 percent from the same 1997 period, according to
company statistics.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that the insurer's life insurance premiums
surged 55.4 percent in the first quarter to 12 billion yuan, with
premiums for property insurance up 6.65 percent to 9.57 billion
yuan and those for re-insurance rocketing 83 percent to 970
million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Also in the first quarter, the PICC paid out 8.09 billion yuan
in insurance claims, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
Company chairman Ma Yongwei said at a recent meeting that the
good business results of his company in the first quarter, which
is normally a rather slow season for insurance, came mainly out of
internal reforms and increased efforts to launch new services,
which include insurance for construction projects and
installation, housing and product quality.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the PICC wrote new life insurance policies valued at
8.1 billion yuan in the first three months for 59 million people,
up 9.8 percent over a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
