<HEADLINE> Philippines to Get Bells from U.S. Before June 12: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Foreign Affairs
Secretary Domingo Siazon Friday said he was almost certain that
the Philippines will recover two controversial bells from the
United States before the June 12 independence centennial
celebration.
</P>
<P>
Siazon, who arrived here from the U.S. on Wednesday, gave the
assurance in reaction to news reports that even if a compromise
solution may have already been found, the bells may not be
recovered in time for the centennial observance.
</P>
<P>
According to the Presidential Palace, U.S. President Bill
Clinton has pledged his "best efforts" to Philippine President
Fidel Ramos during their meeting in Washington last weekend to
secure the return of the bells.
</P>
<P>
The bells were taken as war booty by U.S. soldiers from a
village in Eastern Samar at the height of the Filipino-American
War in 1901. The bells were used by Filipino fighters in alerting
their forces on the advance of American troops in their community.
</P>
<P>
The descendants of the U.S. soldiers who died in the war
opposed the return of the bells.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Ramos and Clinton had agreed on a
compromise arrangement, according to which, the Philippines and
the U.S. will each have one original unit of the two bells and a
replica copy each to settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
Siazon said the Philippine government is willing to spend for
the replication of the bells, if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
