<HEADLINE> APEC Holds Science, Technology Roundtable Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian International
Trade and Industry Minister Rafidah Aziz said Friday the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) should look at
developments in science and technology not only from within the
region but also in the global context.
</P>
<P>
APEC does not only strategize for intra-APEC cooperation in
science and technology but also seeks any form of cooperation with
others outside APEC in areas that can actually benefit APEC
members, the minister said at the opening of the Science,
Engineering and Technology Roundtable Meeting on the APEC Agenda
for Science and Technology Industry Cooperation into the 21st
Century here Friday.
</P>
<P>
She said that there was certainly much that was already
available within APEC in terms of scientific engineering and
technology development which could spur accelerated progress for
individual APEC member economies.
</P>
<P>
"However, there are also developments outside of APEC, such as
in Europe, that will result in breakthroughs that will
revolutionize current technology and have a global impact," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The APEC Agenda for Science and Technology Industry Cooperation
into the 21st Century is being mooted as an action program for
science and technology in APEC.
</P>
<P>
It must be translated into cooperative programs that would
benefit all 21 APEC economies, Rafidah said, adding this
particularly referred to access to new technology already
available in the APEC region, but the members should not expect
any handouts under the agenda.
</P>
<P>
The three-day roundtable meeting, organized by the Institution
of Engineers, Malaysia, in cooperation with the Academy of
Sciences Malaysia, is a preparatory meeting of the APEC Agenda for
Science and Technology Industry Cooperation into the 21st Century,
which will be tabled at this year's APEC Economic Leaders Meeting
to be held here from November 17 to 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
