<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Allow Foreigners to Run 4 Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Finance Ministry would
allow foreign banks to take a 100-percent stake in four banks
taken over by the state in January.
</P>
<P>
The move would serve as an incentive to efficiency in
management of the banks and boost inflow of foreign capital into
Thailand which is suffering from a liquidity crunch.
</P>
<P>
A senior Finance Ministry official on Friday confirmed press
reports that the ministry would waive the current 10-year foreign
share-holding limit for the four banks to pave way for the move
towards a 100-percent share-holding.
</P>
<P>
Lifting the share-holding limit would be a key element for any
successful sale of the banks to foreign institutions.
</P>
<P>
Under the present regulation, foreign share-holders can hold a
majority stake in local financial institutions, but after 10
years, any new share issue would have to be offered to local
investors.
</P>
<P>
As required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Thai
government must announce by mid-year how it will privatize the
four ailing banks taken over by the state -- First Bangkok City
Bank, Bangkok Metropolitan Bank, Bangkok Bank of Commerce and Siam
City Bank.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said earlier that the Finance Ministry is
considering the change because of Thailand's past experience in
managing ailing financial institutions. Both Siam City Bank and
First Bangkok City Bank, for example, had been bailed out by the
government in the past before the January takeover.
</P>
<P>
However, the government takeover of the banks failed to lead to
any improvements in operational efficiency or management.
</P>
<P>
Foreign banks could better develop the ailing firms by
introducing new technology and efficient management which would
help boost their overall stability in the long-term, the official
said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
An announcement on the fate of the four banks is expected
within the next several months, according to press reports Friday.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
