<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Seeking Compensation in Wild Animals Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Three farmers in northeast
China's Jilin Province have asked the local government to
compensate them for three cows that were eaten by a wild Siberian
tiger in the Changbai Mountains early this year.
</P>
<P>
Wang Haiyun, attorney for the farmers, was told by the Jilin
Province Higher People's Court that the proper jurisdiction for
the suit was against the local government in Jiaohe City People's
Court. The Jilin court also said the farmers' attorney could seek
compensation directly from the local government.
</P>
<P>
Wu Songlin, mayor of Jiaohe City, said in an interview with
Xinhua today that "so far we have not received any information on
the suit."
</P>
<P>
The mayor added that "the tiger-eats-cow issue will be solved
according to law."
</P>
<P>
The Jilin provincial people's congress adopted a law in 1996
that local government will pay those whose crops or domestic
animals been damaged for protecting wild animals.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Zhengjie, expert on wild animals, said the planned suit
could be a landmark decision on the protection of wild animals.
</P>
<P>
Since August of 1997, at least 12 cows were eaten by wild
tigers in the Changbai Mountains. A United Nations-funded,
Sino-foreign investigation declared that four-to-six wild tigers
are residing in the Jilin part of the Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The three farmers, whose cows were eaten by tigers in the
maintains, have asked the village and township governments to
offer them 6,000 yuan (720 U.S. dollars) to pay for their property
loss. However, they have not received any reply.
</P>
<P>
The three then invited Wang Haiyun, who is considered one of
"China's Top Ten Lawyers" to be their agent.
</P>
<P>
Li Yi, one of the three farmers, said they are glad that the
tigers under top-level state protection have reappeared in his
area, adding: "We protect tigers and our interest should also be
guaranteed at the same time."
</P>
<P>
Hearing the news that farmers' cows were eaten by tigers, some
ventures and individuals have expressed the will to pay for the
farmers' loss.
</P>
<P>
However, Wang said, this suit must be lodged as it is not a
simple issue of farmers' compensation, but a test of the country's
legal system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0184 </DOCNO>
