<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has exported over 220,000
tons of coffee beans in the 1997-1998 crop year, becoming the
world's fourth biggest coffee exporter after Brazil, Colombia and
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The country gained an export revenue of 340 million
U.S. dollars in this period, an increase of 40 percent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is aimed at raising the country's total coffee acreage
to 350,000 hectares from the current 295,400 hectares, with an
estimated annual output of 450,000 tons of coffee beans by 2005.
