<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Declining Utilization Worries Nigerian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The capacity utilization in
Nigeria's manufacture sector declined from last year's 33 percent
to 25 percent in the first quarter of this year, media reports
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Ralph Alabi, vice-chairman of the Ikeja Branch of the
Manufacturers Association of Nigeria said at a business luncheon
Thursday that a survey of 100 companies show that the capacity
utilization hovered around 35 percent in January and February.
</P>
<P>
The relatively high utilization, he said, was due to the
euphoria generated by the government's 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
However, "Beginning from the month of March, the slow manner
of implementation of the budget began to take its toll on the
economy", he said, noting that the utilization rate slumped to
under 25 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Alabi criticized the poor performance of the country's ports,
where goods were piled up and the 48-hour ultimatum given for the
clearance of goods remained a mirage.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to speed up the privatization of
public parastatals, such as the National Electric Power Authority
and the Nigerian Telecommunications Limited, as promised in the
budget.
</P>
<P>
Other speakers agreed with him, saying that poor
infrastructure, including epileptic water and power supply, is
creating an unfavorable climate for business development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
