<HEADLINE> Portugal Responsible for Smooth Transition in Macao: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres said here Friday that Portugal will take a responsible
attitude to ensure a smooth transition in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The PM made the remarks upon his arrival at noon today for a
three-day visit to Macao en route to his official visit to China's
inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"I pledge again that Portugal will take a responsible attitude
to make sure that a smooth transition will be achieved in Macao,"
he said, adding "so that everybody can face their future with full
confidence and freedom."
</P>
<P>
Guterres said he has full confidence himself in the future of
Macao, and he is deeply convinced that the Sino-Portuguese Joint
Declaration signed by China and Portugal in 1987 will be
implemented.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Macao will continue to be a place of stability,
harmony, prosperity and freedom," he said. "Macao is already an
open and multiple society, and enjoys wide autonomy in its
administration and legislation. Such a structure will be kept
under the Special Administrative Region after 1999."
</P>
<P>
Coming along with the prime minister are dozens of businessmen
and six cabinet ministers, including Foreign Minister Jaime Gama,
Economic Affairs Minister Pina Moura, Science and Technology
Minister Mariano Gago.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, the prime minister is scheduled to meet
leading officials of the Macao Government, the bishop of Macao
Diocese, leaders of local major communities and Chinese officials
stationed in Macao. He will also inaugurate the Macao
Museum.  
</P>
