<HEADLINE> Korean Talks in China Deadlocked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) - The first Korean government talks
are at a standstill again, according to the Republic of Korea's
chief delegate Jeong Se Hyun.
</P>
<P>
Jeong said in a media release, his first since the talks
started here April 11, that he hopes there will be a change in
North Korea's position and suggested that the North contact them
if there is any development.
</P>
<P>
Delegates of the two side had a fruitless morning session and a
dinner meeting on Thursday, and a 95-minute closed-door session
this morning.
</P>
<P>
"To our dismay, there was no change in North Korea's previous
position," Jeong said, and added that what matters most is that
the substance of the matter be dealt with on a basis of
reciprocity.
</P>
<P>
He said that the North attempted to clarify the issue of
fertilizer for the North and hinted at a deal for reuniting
separated families. North-South talks on the family issue started
in 1971 and continued until 1973 with some progress, but
eventually came to nothing because of the lack of a timetable, he
said.
</P>
<P>
A reunion center was clearly prescribed in the 1992 Basic
Agreement's Article 15, Clause 3, he explains.
</P>
<P>
A source at the ROK embassy says that it is difficult to say
when the Beijing talks will conclude, and the embassy of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea has issued no media release
on the talks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
