<HEADLINE> Beijing University Centenary Celebrations Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 15 (Xinhua) -- Beijing University centenary
celebrations began today with a forum on Marxist development,
because "Marxism is the soul of the university," explains Ren
Yanshen, secretary of the Chinese Communist Party Committee in the
university.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 officials and scholars are attending the forum on
Communism's past, present and future, where they said they will
build Beijing University into a center for spreading Marxism in
the next century.
</P>
<P>
The university's birthday on May 4 is expected to be a major
holiday with banners and posters. There is even a countdown clock
in front of the south gate of the university. "Our department has
prepared a lot for the celebrations," says Xiong Meijuan, a
politics major.
</P>
<P>
Construction has been going on in the university since last
year. A centenary hall, a library, a museum, and teaching
buildings are all under construction, which will help provide a
solid basis for development in the 21st century, according to Chen
Zhangliang, vice-president of the university.
</P>
<P>
He explains that the celebrations will be enthusiastic but
simple and will respect academic tradition. Some 40,000 alumni are
expected to return for the celebrations. The university has
graduated 190,000 students since it opened as China's first
state-run university.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 foreign dignitaries, including the presidents
of the U.S.'s Stanford and Britain's Oxford, as well as Nobel
Prize winners, will take part in the celebrations.
</P>
<P>
The university will hold a ceremony at the Great Hall of the
People in Beijing and a series of activities in the university, an
asteroid will be named after a Beijing University scholar, and the
United Nations will distribute stamps for the anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Alumni have already been holding celebrations elsewhere. Hong
Kong alums say they will rent an airplane to come to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University is famous for starting the "May 4" movement
in 1919 which introduced democracy and science to China. It was
also where Marxism was first studied and spread in the country,
and an important base for the Chinese Communist Party in the
1920s. It is, as well, the home of many of China's greatest
scholars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
