<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 09:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Opposition Urges Government to Enter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese rightwing National
Liberal Party leader Dory Chamoun has urged the government to
negotiate with Israel over its withdrawal offer from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star newspaper Friday quoting Chamoun as saying that
negotiating with Israelis did not mean accepting Israeli
conditions detrimental to Lebanon's interests.
</P>
<P>
Such negotiations should be held under U.N. auspices, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also urged all the parties concerned to call for a role of
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in helping implement the
Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
Chamoun observed that Israel was determined to withdraw from
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On April 1, Israeli cabinet endorsed Resolution 425, saying
that it would pull back its troops from south Lebanon if Beirut
agreed on its negotiated security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its northern
villages and towns from Lebanese guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria which has great influence on Lebanon, flatly
rejected Israel's withdrawal offer, arguing that the
U.N. resolution calls for an immediate and unconditional Israeli
withdrawal and does not provide for any negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The resolution 425 was adopted after Israeli first invasion of
Lebanon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Syria, with 40,000 troops deployed in Lebanon as peacekeepers,
was accused by Israel of holding south Lebanon as "a bargaining
chip" in forcing it to return Golan Heights Syria lost to Israel
in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Chamoun also criticized Lebanese officials for what he
considered an exaggerated reliance on Syria to solve their
problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
