<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh May Depend more on Wheat: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A well-known agricultural expert
has said Bangladesh may have to depend more on wheat in the future
to feed its increasing population, The Financial Express daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Norman E. Borlaug, a Nobel Laureate and a senior consultant
with the Mexico-based International Maize and Wheat Improvement
Center, said this while giving a lecture on food security at a
symposium titled "Vision for Agricultural Research and
Development" held here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Though Bangladesh had made a great success in increasing rice
production, but the country "many have to depend more on wheat in
the future to feed its ever growing population," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The farmers in Bangladesh, he noted, "have already responded to
the need by expanding and intensifying wheat production in the
winter season."
</P>
<P>
Yields of wheat increased with national wheat area expanding
rapidly -- from 125,000 hectares in 1976 to 600,000 hectares in
1981 -- and the production multiplied ever since, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1996-97 season, the country had a record wheat harvest
of nearly 1.7 million tons from 700,000 hectares, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I understand that the 1997-98 crop will probably be better
than last year," he said, adding that some 1.9 million tons are
expected from 800,000 hectares this season with an average yield
of 2.4 tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
While rice is certainly the preferred staple, more than 2.5
million tons of wheat are consumed annually in Bangladesh,
according to the symposium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
