<HEADLINE> Peace Talks on Sudan Set to Resume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiations between the
Khartoum government and southern Sudanese rebels will resume in
Nairobi on April 30, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which broke off in November, are aimed at ending 14
years of civil war in the largest African country, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Ali al-Haj Mohammed, the Deputy Secretary General of the
Sudanese National Congress, the country's only legal political
organization, was quoted as saying Thursday in Khartoum that the
Kenyan government has informed the Sudanese government about the
exact date for the talks.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Foreign Ministry said earlier Thursday that peace
negotiations between the Khartoum government and southern
Sudanese rebels would resume in Nairobi during the last week of
April.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed did not give details on the government delegation
that is to attend the Nairobi talks, nor whether he would himself
attend.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that Khartoum would broach the issue of the
country's draft constitution which, he said, was in response to
southern Sudanese demands for self-determination and guarantees
of liberties.
</P>
<P>
In early November, delegations representing the Muslim-ruled
government of President Omar al-Bashir and the Sudan People's
Liberation Army (SPLA) met for 10 days here under the auspices of
the regional Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD).
</P>
<P>
The two sides were meeting then for the first time since 1994.
Their war has dragged on since 1983 when the SPLA re-started
fighting for more autonomy and religion freedom in the animist
and Christian dominated south.  
</P>
</TEXT>
