<HEADLINE> China Gets Its First Housing Price Index </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The State Development Planning
Commission and the State Statistics Bureau yesterday issued a real
estate and housing price index for the first time, according to
today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
The three-part index covers housing sales, land transfers and
housing rents. The housing sales price index is 101.3, that of
land transfers is 101.7, and for housing rents, 103.7.
</P>
<P>
The index is based on the corresponding quarter of last year,
with a benchmark of 100.
</P>
<P>
The comparatively higher housing rent rate is related to
housing reforms and a rapid rise in housing rents, the two
departments say. They predict that with increasing housing
reforms, the housing sales index will drop and that for rents will
go up.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the average price of a sq.m. of commercial housing was
1,766 yuan, and in large and medium-sized cities, up to 3,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
People in the industry say that the price is still too high,
and that, to push housing construction and make it a force for
economic development, the country has to improve its real estate
price controls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
