<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Main Opposition Names Shadow Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Mwai Kibaki, the chairman of
Kenya's main opposition Democratic Party (DP), has named a
20-member shadow cabinet to articulate DP policies on national
issues.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki, also the leader of the opposition in the parliament,
appears himself under the "office of the president," but his
specific duties are not spelt out.
</P>
<P>
The move should get parliamental members loyal to DP to focus
on specific areas in national affairs, said Kibaki Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki said he could not form a shadow coalition cabinet of
opposition lawmakers because "the law does not allow this and the
realities of the day are such that we could not find a party to
work with."
</P>
<P>
Late Thursday, DP lawmaker Martha Karua, who was named shadow
minister for home affairs, national heritage, culture and social
services, declined the role, saying she was not consulted.
</P>
<P>
"I feel that the manner in which the appointment was made,
with all the attendant lobbying and manipulations, makes it
difficult for me to accept the appointment," she said.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki took the second place after current President Daniel
arap Moi in Kenya's second multi-pary general elections held at
the end of December, 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
