<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Airlines to Suspend Two Flights to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Airlines, which is
headquartered in Chicago, said Thursday that it will suspend two
flights to South Korea because of the recent Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The daily non-stop service between San Francisco and South
Korea's capital of Seoul will be suspended as from May 5, while
the service between the Japanese city of Osaka and Seoul will also
be suspended from July 8, said the company.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reason for the suspension, Chris Bowers, vice
president of the airlines, said in a company newsletter that "we
have been unable to achieve sustained profitability on these
routes" because South Korea has been particularly hard hit during
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Richard Martin, the company spokesman, said the airlines
already eliminated other Asian routes in recent months, including
those from Guam to Osaka and Manila to Seoul.
</P>
<P>
But he pointed out that there are other Asian routes which had
been added or increased, including more than doubling the weekly
flights between Chicago and Tokyo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
