<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Company Develops New Embalming Material </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A new discovery in China is
expected to replace formalin, which has been used for a long time,
for embalming bodies, either humans or animals in museums.
</P>
<P>
After experimenting with a substance used to preserve corpses
during the Ming Dynasty (1368 to 1644), Chinese began to produce
it in the city of Nanjing in Jiangsu Province and managed to
preserve a body for half a year with the new technique.
</P>
<P>
Li Xingguo of Nanjing's Suyi Biological Embalming Factory said
that the discovery will change embalming significantly.
</P>
<P>
Formalin can have some bad effects on those working with it and
they are not allowed to come into contact with it. But, the new
process involves immersing the body in epoxy resin and polymers
for at least a week, after which it is placed on a special bed for
hardening.
</P>
<P>
The new method is considered better than formaldehyde treatment
for another reason, because the plasticized body does not have a
bad odor, it is non-toxic, and it cannot be damaged easily.
</P>
<P>
The technique has been used by Hong Kong University and the
Guangdong College of Pharmacy, and a number of medical colleges in
Beijing, Shanghai and other big cities are preparing to establish
new labs for using the method. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
