<HEADLINE> Angola Clears Zambia Over Support for Angolan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Angola has exculpated Zambia from
accusations of supplying arms to the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), an official of the Organization
of African Unity (OAU) said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
OAU assistant secretary general Daniel Antonio said that the
Angolan government has assured him that Zambia has not involved
in the alleged arms deal with UNITA, according to Times of
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Antonio, who held talks with both the Angolan government and
UNITA in Luanda before arriving here, said the OAU has not
received any official information on the alleged arms deals.
</P>
<P>
He said his mission to Angola and now Zambia is basically to
discuss the implementation process of the Lusaka Protocol signed
in 1994 by the Angolan government and UNITA.
</P>
<P>
"I met UNITA and the Angolan government and left Luanda more
encouraged. We now hope to see how Zambia can continue to support
the implementation of the peace process in Angola," Antonio said.
</P>
<P>
Angolan ambassador to Zambia Manuel Augusto charged on March 5
that Zambians are supplying arms to UNITA through Zambia.
</P>
<P>
He warned that whilst his country does not wish to have a
repeat of the Congo-Brazzavile and Congo Kinshasa incidents where
the Angolan government participated in dislodging the governments
there, "Angola does not rule out any option if UNITA does not
stop getting arms from some territories."
</P>
<P>
But Zambian president Frederick Chiluba on March 12 denied
that his government has any involvement in the supply of arms to
any country.
</P>
<P>
The president however said that his government will investigae
allegations that Zambia is being used as a transit point for arms
to UNITA, which fought a civil war of about 20 years against the
Angolan government after the country's independence in 1976.
</P>
</TEXT>
