<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Role Of Press As Watchdog Growing In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- When several officials in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region were revealed by the
newspaper China Youth Daily earlier this month to be using their
power for extravagant wining and dining, the scandal led to a
clean-government drive in the region.
</P>
<P>
Cao Bochun, the autonomous region's Party chief, says that
problems need to be seen correctly and that the press should be
supported in its critical role. In today's China, more people are
taking a look at things in society.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say that the press in China is increasing its
role in the anti-corruption drive, and in ethical and cultural
progress and establishing the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview, the Chairman of the National People's
Congress Li Peng urged the press to criticise government mistakes
and shortcomings more, and to expose corruption.
</P>
<P>
When Li visited Central TV earlier this year, he made special
mention of the program "Focus", which airs during prime time, and
which is supposed to draw the public's attention towards
corruption and the bad side of society.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection
of the Chinese Communist Party recently praised the press in its
fight against corruption in the past several years and said that
this year, there will be better conditions for press
participation, and more cases of corruption will be made public by
the press.
</P>
<P>
In a recent meeting, Xiao Yang, the President of the Supreme
People's Court, said that the courts across China need to put
themselves under the scrutiny of the press. All trials, except
those involving privacy, national security and a few others,
should be open, he said, and the press should be permitted to
cover them.
</P>
<P>
In order to encourage journalists to do better work, the All
China Journalists Association is now preparing to set up a special
committee to protect the rights of journalists.
</P>
<P>
Journalists should have access to support when their rights or
their lives are in danger, says one association official, and this
needs improvement.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, many representatives at the
Ninth National People's Congress said that a law on supervision
should be formulated as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
