<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Records Low Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Prices in New Zealand rose
only 0.2 percent in the first quarter this year, lower than
expected by market forecasts and the Reserve Bank.
</P>
<P>
Television New Zealand reported on Friday that the quarterly
consumer price index (CPI) put inflation in the year ending March
to 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank had expected the first quarter CPT to rise 0.4
percent, and economists had tipped on average 0.5 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Food prices, which went up sharply in the quarter because of a
drought, are the main contributor to the CPI increase. But CPI was
held down by lower petrol prices, cheaper international airfares
and lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The report expects that the low inflation will prompt the
Reserve Bank to further ease its monetary policy in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
The lower-than-expected CPI triggered off a fall on the
interest rates with the 90-day bill rates dropping nearly half a
percentage point to just over 9 percent shortly after the figure
was released.  
</P>
</TEXT>
