<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Long-Term Development Goal for Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) --China has decided to build a power
industry set-up compatible with the development demands of a
modernized country by year 2050, today's "Economic Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the development goal would be
realized in three stages. On the basis of having a total installed
generating capacity of 290 million kilowatts (kw) and producing
1,400 billion kw/hours of electricity annually by 2000, China will
speed up power construction to increase its total installed
generating capacity to 500 million kw by 2010.
</P>
<P>
By then, a gigantic power production center will be in
operation at the Three Gorges Dam, and three large power grids --
north, central and south -- will be interconnected, with
electricity expected to be available in all rural
villages. Technical and economic indexes for power would be close
to advanced international standards.
</P>
<P>
China should have an installed generating capacity of
700-to-800 million kw by 2020, and expects to have in place a
rational structure of hydropower, thermal power, nuclear power and
new energy. It plans to form a nationwide united power grid, as
well as a rational distribution and sustainable development of
power resources in the country, eventually reaching the goal by
2050.
</P>
<P>
To realize the goal, efforts should be made to adjust the power
industry's internal structure and optimize resource distribution,
intensifying power-grid construction and advancing a nationwide
connection of power grids, an official with the China State Power
Corp. said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Maintain 9 Percent Economic Growth in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Governments at all levels and
concerned departments in the Chinese capital have been called on
to guarantee a 9 percent economic growth rate in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Jia Qinglin, secretary of the Beijing Municipal Committee of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) and also the city's mayor, was
quoted by today's Beijing Daily as saying that it is imperative to
combine economic growth with economic returns, further deepen
the reform and make unremitting efforts to help state enterprises
improve their condition.
</P>
<P>
He said that it is of important political significance to
achieve this target since it has an important bearing on achieving
an 8 percent economic growth rate for the country.
</P>
<P>
Jia made these remarks at a meeting Thursday analyzing
Beijing's economic growth in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in the first three months of this year,
Beijing realized 31.32 billion yuan (3.77 billion U.S. dollars) in
gross domestic product, 9.17 percent higher than that for the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter, retail sales hit a record 27.46
billion yuan (3.31 billion U.S. dollars), an increase of 14
percent; revenues came to 6.14 billion yuan (739 million
U.S. dollars), up by 26.5 percent; increases of 9.45 percent and
6.6 percent were reported in per-capita wages of urban workers and
in the per-capital income of rural residents, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The city introduced 940 million U.S. dollars in foreign funds
in real terms, representing an increase of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, 67 key projects -- most of which are urban
infrastructural facilities -- are under construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
