<HEADLINE> Zambia to Rehabilitate Major Railway Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will spend 91 billion
Kwacha (about 50 million U.S. Dollars) to rehabilitate the
railway from Kitwe to Livingstone.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia Friday quoted Managing Director of Zambia
Railway (ZR) Robert Crawford as saying in Kabwe in central Zambia
Thursday that the program will start in about six weeks and run
for five years.
</P>
<P>
He said funds will have to be sourced from the World Bank and
other international donors, internal resources and the
government.
</P>
<P>
"We are under extreme financial pressure, but the
rehabilitation program will have to start. We are determined that
in six weeks, funds will be sourced," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the financial problems have been worsened with the
decline in traffic as the biggest single customer, ZCCM (Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines) has had its copper prices reduced on
the world metal market.
</P>
<P>
The current wooden sleepers will have to replaced with
concrete ones and the locomotives will have to be repaired, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The company expects to spend seven billion Kwacha on spare
parts every year, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the present 5,100 workforce, Crawford said the company is
looking for ways to improve manpower efficiency and did not rule
out the possibility of retrenching some of the employees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
