<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Quarter Industrial, Commercial Taxes up 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The China State Administration of
Taxation announced today that the country's industrial and
commercial tax income in the first quarter reached 172.36 billion
yuan, up 15.67 billion yuan or 10 percent from the same quarter
last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total tax income in the quarter, domestic value-added
and consumption taxes contributed 87.64 billion yuan, up 2.6
percent from the same period last year; the business tax levy
climbed 30.9 percent to 37.94 billion yuan; while taxes from
foreign investments, stamps and other local levies grew by more
than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, taxes declined from resources, collectively owned
enterprises' incomes and imports. The tax rebates to export
companies in the quarter were 4.66 billion yuan, up 16.2 percent
from the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
Tax income of the central government and local governments grew
at the same pace. The central government collected taxes of 92.96
billion yuan in the quarter, an increase of 9.7 percent, while
local governments collected 79.4 billion yuan, up 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The administration indicated that the growth rate of tax
collection during the quarter slowed compared to the same periods
of the last two years. The main reason cited was a decrease in
taxes from some key industries.
</P>
<P>
Taxes from petroleum, petrochemicals, coal and sugar dropped
more than 10 percent. This was attributed to the Southeast Asian
financial crisis, fluctuating oil prices in the global market and
restructuring of state-owned enterprises among other factors.
</P>
</TEXT>
