<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johansson Says Rotation System Better for Host Selection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A rotation system among
confederations should replace the present bidding system for
selection of the future World Cup finals host, UEFA President
Lennart Johansson said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
When asked about a proposal to allow only one country per
continent to bid for future World Cup finals, Johansson said it is
up to the FIFA ruling Executive Committee to decide whether to
adopt it.
</P>
<P>
"But I personally think a rotation system among the
confederations could solve the problem," Johansson told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said he was concerned about the amount of campaign money
spent in the bidding system while a rotation system could save all
that.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch soccer association has proposed that one nation be
nominated from each confederation to be put forward as potential
hosts for future FIFA competition.
</P>
<P>
The German soccer federation, which is at present competing
with their English counterpart in the race for the 2006 World Cup
finals, said on Thursday that it had set aside 20 million marks
($11 million) to promote its bid.
</P>
<P>
Johansson told a news conference upon his arrival here that he
would advocate "transparency, democracy and solidarity" if he is
elected FIFA president in June.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the `United Nations of football'. I believe in
transparency. I believe in solidarity. If I become FIFA
President, I would prove that is not election tactics," said
Johansson, who is vying for the presidency against the other
candidate, FIFA General-Secretary Sepp Blatter.
</P>
<P>
He denied he had called Blatter "a puppet" of the reigning
President Joao Havelange in the previous war of words.
</P>
<P>
"That was not what I said." he said. "Dr. Havelange, whom I
highly respect, has served in the world football for more than 20
years. He was the right man in the right place in the right time."
</P>
<P>
"Among all these insults that I have to take from the president
today, he said I was a puppet-on-the-string of Germany and I only
went their way," he added.
</P>
<P>
Johansson said he respected Blatter as a candidate but "could
not respect after knowing he started campaign in Asia months ago."
</P>
<P>
"He never stood up in the ring," the European soccer boss
added. "He said 'perhaps', 'perhaps', 'not', 'perhaps'. Finally
the President announced Blatter's candidacy."
</P>
<P>
Johansson said, "Then with reference to what the President said
about me, I wonder who is the 'puppet-on-the-string.'"
</P>
<P>
FIFA will decide its new president on June 8 in its 51st
Congress in Paris, two days before the start of the World Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launching New Securities Investment Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China will launch its third
securities investment fund on April 22, in another move to develop
institutional investors in the securities market.
</P>
<P>
The "Xinghua Fund" is expected to issue two billion units at a
face value of one yuan. The sponsors, the Beijing-based China
Securities Co. Ltd., the Beijing Securities Co. Ltd., and the
China Science and Technology International Trust and Investment
Co. Ltd. are expected to purchase 60 million units. The remaining
1.94 billion units will be offered to the public through the Shanghai
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The closed-end fund has a 15-year term and will invest its
capital in stocks and treasury bonds. The China Construction Bank
will be the custodian.
</P>
<P>
This shows the determination of securities authorities to
standardize and stabilize the market through institutional
investors, market analysts say.
</P>
<P>
The new fund's manager, the China Fund Management Co. Ltd.,
says it will run the fund in a standard way and minimize risks by
setting up two special committees to make investment and
risk-prevention decisions.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard the fund, the China Construction Bank has also set
up a new department staffed with high-calibre personnel, stronger
internal controls, advanced technology, and a market surveillance
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Tightening May Help Solve Currency Woes in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The prevailing credit tightening
scheme and the high interest rates imposed by commercial banks may
help solve the currency crisis in the Philippines, an economist
said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine News Agency reported on Friday that Emilio
Antonio, a senior economics professor at the University of Asia
and the Pacific, made the assessment in his study.
</P>
<P>
Antonio admitted that the economy can not be bailed out of its
present situation by simply tightening credit and raising interest
rates, but he agreed that the policies are normally recommended to
stabilize the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The only thing the monetary authorities must do is to keep the
credit tightening and high interest rate policies within
reasonable levels, he said in the study.
</P>
<P>
After the financial storm swept Southeast and East Asian
nations, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) required these
countries to tighten credit and raise interest rates while
providing financial assistances to them.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF's medicines gradually became unpopular in
these nations. In the Philippines, some economists said the
policies dealt a severe blow to the manufacturing sector and would
dampen the growth of economy in the long run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
