<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP, Zimbabwe Working on Local Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Programe (UNDP) and Zimbabwe are working together to formulate a
project document on the sustainable use of traditional medicines,
a UNDP official said Thursday, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
UNDP resident representative Carlos Lopes told a workshop in
Kadoma of central Zimbabwe on biodiversity the project was being
handled in a professional manner together with the Zimbabwean
ministry of mines, environment and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Lopes said there was need for Zimbabwe to patent some of its
medicines to protect its intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Most African countries were failing to access medicines from
the continent being sold overseas because they had to seek
permission from patent holders there, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Concern is increasing that uncontrolled access to forest
resources could be abused by outsiders especially in the case of
plants with intrinsic medicinal and economic value," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This can be avoided by instituting comprehensive and
effective legislative and monitoring mechanisms that recognise
intellectual property rights of the local people," Lopes said.
</P>
<P>
Lopes said there was need for Zimbabwe to sign conventions it
was familiar with to avoid misunderstandings in future.
</P>
<P>
He said there was a tendency to emphasise one component of
biological resources like wildlife at the expense of others.
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive strategy, he said, should take into account
the physical, cultural, spiritual and economic needs of the
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
