<HEADLINE> Korean Talks Reopen; No Progress Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) - The inter-Korean talks adjourned
again following a reportedly fruitless closed-door session here
this morning.
</P>
<P>
"Little progress has been made, but we agreed to keep contact,"
said Chun Kum Chul, chief delegate of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), after the 100-minute working-level
session at the hotel where the Republic of Korea (ROK) delegation
stays.
</P>
<P>
"It's true, no progress is in sight so far," a source from the
ROK embassy said when asked to comment on a report that both sides
made a breakthrough last night on the issues of helping reunite
separated families and supplying fertilizer to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
The source confirmed a new proposal by the DPRK delegation that
the ROK ship 200,000 tons of fertilizer to the DPRK by the end of
May, saying: "No agreement has been signed, as the South would add
conditions to the shipment."
</P>
<P>
The ROK still insisted that the DPRK fix a date for
establishing a meeting place to help facilitate reunions of
the separated families.
</P>
<P>
Sources claimed that both sides had agreed in principle to hold
Red Cross talks this month to discuss details for helping reunite
families.
</P>
<P>
The morning session, with the two head delegates attending, was
aimed at narrowing the differences following a fruitless dinner
meeting last night.  
</P>
</TEXT>
