<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Huge Investment Aids Human Gene Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The National Natural Science Fund
Committee has decided to allocate another seven million yuan
(875,000 US dollars) in the next three years to a human genome
project to ensure that the research remains on the cutting edge in
the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The funding is the committee's biggest among its research
projects during the Ninth Five-Year Plan period from 1996 to
2,000, according to today's Wenhui Daily based in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The project, "Studies on Several Gene Loci Structure of the
Chinese Human Genome," was initiated in 1994 and comprises three
sub-projects.
</P>
<P>
The sub-projects include building a bank of immortalized cell
lines to reserve genes from representative ethnic groups and
endangered ethnic minorities, introducing and upgrading new
techniques of human gene science and studying the position of the
gene related to human diseases.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the project said they have made substantial
progress, which has laid the foundation for forming a cooperative
system for human gene studies in China.
</P>
<P>
With 22 percent of the world's total population, 56 different
ethnic groups and several isolated ethnic communities, China has
the diseases common among people in developing countries as well
as those associated with modern lifestyles such as heart disease
and certain types of cancer found in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
All these are considered good resources for the study of
diversity in human genes as well as human vulnerability and
antibodies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
