<HEADLINE> South America Walking Towards Economic Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The South American Common
Market (Mercosur) and the Andean Group Thursday signed a framework
agreement on establishing a free trade zone by the year 2000, a
step closer to the regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from member countries of the two groups,
including Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay, Uruguay, Ecuador, Bolivia,
Colombia, Peru and Venezuela, signed the agreement in the
Argentine capital.
</P>
<P>
The two groups have a population of 300 million and a total GDP
of one trillion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The framework agreement, which will replace all the existing
agreements between the two sides, will gradually eliminate trade
tariffs and barriers within the proposed free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, negotiations on preferential tariffs
should be finished before September 30.
</P>
<P>
Ultimately, the two groups should reach a concrete agreement on
tariff reductions and elimination by the end of the century, so
that the free trade zone can take off in 2000.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed the establishment of the trade zone will
speed up the formation of the cross-America free trade zone, also
known as ALCA.
</P>
<P>
The merger will also fortify the negotiating weight and
positions of the two groups in regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem, who hosted the signing
ceremony, said the merger was not only an economic but also a
political event with far-reaching effects. The merger was the
first step towards building a South American free trade
zone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
