<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-22 Agrees to Strengthen World Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Finance officials from the
Group of 22 countries and regions agreed on Thursday to strengthen
the international financial system in transparency, market
structure and the role of private sectors in times of crisis.
</P>
<P>
The officials announced the formation of working groups to
contribute to international dialogue on how to proceed in these
areas.
</P>
<P>
United States Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin told the meeting
that creditors, investors and policy makers need more types of
information than in the past because of the complex global
financial markets of today.
</P>
<P>
"They also need to use that information well, and appropriately
balance risks and rewards," he added.
</P>
<P>
A brief statement, issued after the meeting, emphasized that
sound domestic policies are fundamental to healthy and robust
national economies and financial sectors, and increasingly to the
prospects for other countries and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has been the focus of the spring
meetings of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank. Crisis prevention and management are high on the agenda of
the meetings.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the evening, the Interim Committee of the IMF
adopted a series of guidelines in financial crisis prevention and
management.
</P>
<P>
The G-22, created early this year, groups Argentina, Australia,
Brazil, Canada, China, France, Germany, Hong Kong SAR, India,
Indonesia, Italy, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, Poland,
Russia, Singapore, South Africa, Thailand, Britain and the United
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
