<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Adopts Guidelines for Coping With Crises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said on Thursday there was an urgent need to strengthen
the architecture of the international monetary system to prevent
and resolve any Asian-style currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the IMF's policy-setting Interim Committee, at
its 50th meeting, noted that strengthening the monetary system was
needed in light of globalization, which had brought clear benefit,
but at the same time posed challenges.
</P>
<P>
The committee stressed the importance of sound macroeconomic
policies and strong financial systems to guard against
vulnerability to shifts in market sentiment, and the contagious
effects of policy weaknesses in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The committee said action was also needed to strengthen
domestic financial systems by developing supervisory and
regulatory frameworks consistent with internationally accepted
practices, and strengthened standards for bank and non-bank
financial entities.
</P>
<P>
The committee called on the Fund to work with other concerned
institutions and organizations responsible for the development of
standards and guidelines. This would be in areas to consider how
best the Fund could assist in the dissemination of such standards
to the membership and to encourage members to adopt them.
</P>
<P>
The financial officials called for strengthened Fund
surveillance and recommendations. They said the Fund should
intensify its surveillance of financial sector issues and capital
flows, give particular attention to policy interdependence and
risks of contagion, and ensure that it is fully aware of market
views and perspectives.
</P>
<P>
The committee also suggested greater availability and
transparency of information for grading economic data and
policies. It underscored members' obligation to provide timely
and accurate data to the Fund.
</P>
<P>
The committee said the Fund should provide a timely response to
a crisis by playing a central role in crisis management. It
supported the establishment of the Supplemental Reserve Facility
and the use of emergency procedures in the Fund's rapid response
in support of countries in crisis.
</P>
<P>
On other issues, the committee also adopted a code of good
practices on fiscal transparency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
