<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Preventing Fires in China's Largest Forest Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's largest forest zone, in
the Dahinggan Mountains, is on alert against forest fires, and
vehicle checkpoints have been set up at all entrances to check
individuals and motor vehicles entering the forest.
</P>
<P>
There are 12 forest protection airbases in northeastern China
that do overflights every day to spot possible fires and people
living in the zone have to abide by fuel usage regulations
strictly, especially on windy days. And, the forest police are
always on the alert.
</P>
<P>
Because of the El Nino effect, temperatures in the Dahinggan
Mountains at this time of year are two or three degrees higher
than normal. In addition, the ice and snow have melted more
quickly than usual because of dry and windy weather. As a result,
the threat of forest fires is growing, says Shi Yufeng, a fire
control official at the Dahinggan forest office.
</P>
<P>
A very large forest fire broke out in the forest zone in 1987,
and since that time, a number of small fires have been reported,
so the Chinese government is keeping a close eye on fire
prevention in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
