<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Address Waste Problem on Earth Day '98 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- In observance of Earth Day '98,
the Anti-Waste Import Society of Indonesia will hold a public
dialog on Indonesia's role as an importer of waste materials, an
official said.
</P>
<P>
Chairperson of the Earth Day '98 organizing committee Nur
Amalia said here Thursday the dialog will focus on the impact of
foreign waste materials on the Indonesian environment and people,
Antara News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that scavengers are particularly susceptible to
the dangers posed by foreign waste dumped in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Amalia said 40 percent of imported waste products, most of
which contain toxic substances, cannot be recycled and are
therefore a serious threat to man and the environment.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Environmental Impact Assessment Agency found about
500 containers of imported waste at several seaports.
</P>
<P>
The government and the House of Representatives responded
positively to the problem by issuing an environment law in 1997
which banned the import of industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
But environmentalists fear some unscrupulous Indonesians are
still making money by illegally importing waste.
</P>
<P>
To observe this year's Earth Day, artists, intellectuals and
non-governmental organizations under the umbrella of the
Indonesian Alliance for Better Earth and Human Life will hold a
program called "Earth Cleansing to Dispel Disasters". 
</P>
</TEXT>
