<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Adopts Code of Good Practices on Fiscal Transparency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund on Thursday adopted a code of good practices on fiscal
transparency as a step to averting future Asian-style currency
crises.
</P>
<P>
The action by the IMF's policy-setting Interim Committee
followed day-long discussions focusing on preventing and resolving
financial crises.
</P>
<P>
In a 15-page closing communique, the communique said, the new
code would "serve as a guide for members" on increasing the
quality and timeliness of reports on key economic indicators, such
as the amount of foreign debt a country holds, its trade deficit
and the size of its currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the IMF's spring meeting also discussed going much
further to give the institution more power to expose risky
financial practices.
</P>
<P>
The code requests government sector to be clearly distinguished
from the rest of the economy, and policy and management roles
within government should be well defined.
</P>
<P>
Under the code, there should be a clear legal and
administrative framework for fiscal management, and public should
be provided with full information on the past, current and
projected fiscal activity of government.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that budget documentation should specify fiscal
policy objectives, the macroeconomic framework, the policy basis
for the budget, and identifiable major fiscal risks.
</P>
<P>
On other practices, the code said, procedures for the execution
and monitoring of approved expenditures should be clearly
specified; and fiscal reporting should be timely, comprehensive,
reliable, and identify deviations from the budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
