<HEADLINE> Bosnian Croats, Muslims Agree on Refugee Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 16 (Xinhua) -- After months of wrangling, Bosnian
Croat and Muslim officials agreed Thursday on the main rules for
the return of Bosnian refugees to the divided southwestern city of
Mostar.
</P>
<P>
The returnings, to be monitored by international officials, are
expected to begin immediately and unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, repatriation of refugees is to be carried
out in phases, with Bosnian Croats returning to 266 houses in
Muslim-controlled eastern Mostar, and 187 Muslim homes being
reoccupied in the Croat-controlled west.
</P>
<P>
Obstacles preventing the return of the refugees must be removed
soon and the security of the returnees should be guaranteed,
Sadako Ogata, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees,
said in Sarajevo. She had returned from a regional tour of the
republics of former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian refugee problem holds the key to safeguarding peace
and stability in the region and to the successful implementation
of the Daton peace accord, European Union (EU) president Van Den
Broek said on Thursday in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
