<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Decorative Bricks Found In Ancient Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a large number of bricks with moulded designs in
newly-uncovered tombs in northwest China's Shaanxi Province that
are believed to have been made 1,800 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The 4-meter by 2.5-meter tombs are along a two-kilometer
stretch of road. They were built during the early Eastern Han
dynasty (25-220).
</P>
<P>
Ancient craftsmen carved rectangular caves in the rocks to keep
the tombs from the prying eyes of grave robbers, according to
archaeologists, who say that the most attractive thing is their
wall bricks, 50 cm. by 16 cm. by 6 cm., with moulded-on designs of
diamonds, dragons, fish, birds, pillars and palaces. They also say
that using moulded bricks for tomb decorations was quite rare in
early China. Some 1,000 such bricks have been found, the
archaelogists say.
</P>
<P>
A large number of funerary objects were also unearthed, like
pottery cooking utensils, bronze mirrors and ancient coins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
