<HEADLINE> Venezuela, Mexico Sign Energy Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela and Mexico signed an
agreement on Thursday aimed at strengthening the traditional ways
of energy cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed at the "La Casona" presidential
residence by Erwin Arrieta Valera, Venezuelan energy and mines
minister, and Luis Tellez Kuenzler, Mexican energy minister.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Rafael Caldera of Venezuela and Ernesto Zedillo of
Mexico were also present at the signing. Zedillo was ending an
official three-day visit to the South American nation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two countries will cooperate in the
areas of conventional and non-conventional energy sources, and the
efficient use of energy.
</P>
<P>
They will create an advisory group for the purpose of
consultation and the exchange of information on studies and
projects, promoting productivity, efficiency, conservation and
sustainability of the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Venezuela and Mexico is developing rapidly, with
bilateral trade amounting to 717.891 million U.S. dollars in 1997,
a 42.30 percent increase over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
