<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Committee Urges Japan to Lead Asia Out of Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders at an International
Monetary Fund committee meeting Thursday urged Japan to take
decisive action to stimulate their economy in an effort to help
Asia recover from the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said that a sustained
global expansion and recovery in Asia cannot be achieved while
Japan, the second largest economy in the world and accounting for
more than half of Asia's output, is in a recession and suffering
from a weakened financial system.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told the IMF's policy-making interim committee that
"Japan must generate substantial growth to help maintain an
expanding world economy and to absorb a growing share of imports
from emerging markets."
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus also said the
deterioration of Japan's position was clouding Asia's economic
prospects.
</P>
<P>
"To lift the Japanese economy and allow it to support activity
elsewhere in the region, forceful and credible actions are needed
to strengthen confidence, restructure the financial system and
move forward on the structural reform agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Vice Finance Minister Shozaburo Nakamura told the
committee that the Japanese government would do its utmost to help
its economy recover.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, which focused on finding ways to prevent future
crises in Asia, some officials suggested an expanded role for the
IMF, which stepped in with billions of dollars last year to help
out Asia's troubled economies.
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury Minister Carlo Ciampi said the recent crises
have shown that we need better surveillance at the national,
regional and global levels over country macroeconomic policies.
</P>
<P>
The committee meeting also highlighted transparency, the need
to strengthen financial systems and the prospects for global
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Some major industrial countries called for reforms designed to
shore up a global financial system and give the IMF more power to
expose risky financial practices of member countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
