<HEADLINE> Gulf War Compensation Payments In Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
Province has just about completed the first compensation payments
for victims of the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The compensation package amounts to 177,000 US dollars. It was
granted by the United Nations Compensation Committee for 72
employees of the Fushun Foreign Economic Construction Corporation,
who were working in Kuwait when the Gulf War broke out in
1990. Each of the 72 workers received 2,500 US dollars in
compensation.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chengzhi, one of those who was compensated, said that he
still vividly remember the hardship he experienced when he drove
2,000 kilometers in three days in the withdrawal from Kuwait to
Jordan, eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
All the victims in China have received the compensation
payments, and those living overseas, of whom there are three, who
qualify can entrust agents to get the money for them, says Shi
Zhengxin, a corporation official in charge of compensation
payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
