<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican crudes for export registered a slight
rise after Venezuela, Saudi Arabia and Mexico agreed to reduce the
amount of oil extracted.
</P>
<P>
The price of light crude went from 10.63 U.S. dollars to 10.92
dollars per barrel on March 15, while the Olmeca crude rose from
13.56 dollars to 13.93 dollars.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian oil production reached 1.3 million
barrels a day in March, a 1.37 percent increase over the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
The authorities plan to extract 1.7 million barrels a day
during the next five years. Oil consumption totals 1.7 million
barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua banana exporting firms say they have lost
at least 400,000 U.S. dollars recently because of trucks being
blocked by former employees who were affected by an insecticide
used in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The former workers are demanding 10 million dollars for damages
caused by being exposed to nemagon, an insecticide used in the
1970s by the U.S. transnational company Standard Fruit Company.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine agricultural production lost 1.5
billion dollars due to rains and floods caused by the "El Nino"
climate phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The damages affected 10 million hectares in the country and
50,000 producers, said Felipe Sola, minister of agriculture,
livestock, fishing, and food.
</P>
<P>
Sola estimated that Argentina will lose one million tons of
agricultural products in export, especially cotton and sunflower
seeds.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chilean domestic sales of cement increased 13.2
percent during the first quarter of the year, compared with the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sales of the product reached 25.3 million bags in the first
three months, but cement consuming is expected to diminish after
the second quarter because of the deceleration of the real estate
sector.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian government plans to triple the wheat
harvest in the next few years to meet the internal demand and
reduce imports.
</P>
<P>
The wheat harvest is expected to go from 2.3 million tons in
1998 to six million tons.
</P>
<P>
Wheat imports surpass five million tons and national consuming
is eight million tons a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
