<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retrial For Former Italian Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Italy's highest appeals court, the
Court of Cassation, annulled on Thursday an eight-year jail
sentence handed to former Socialist Prime Minister Bettino Craxi
for kickbacks paid on construction work on Milan's metro.
</P>
<P>
Craxi's role in the 50-billion lire (29 million U.S. dollars)
corruption scandal will now be re-examined by Milan's Appeals
court, which upheld the sentence of eight years against Craxi in
June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Craxi, the Italian prime minister from 1983 to 1987, has been
living in self-imposed exile in Tunisia since 1993 when he fled
Italy amid several corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
He was also charged with receiving bribes in the short-lived
Enimont public-private chemicals merger between Eni and
Montedison, and the bankruptcy of the Bank Ambrosiano.
</P>
<P>
In annulling the sentence and ordering a retrial, the Court of
Cassation accepted Craxi's lawyers' argument that a revision in
the penal code made the previous ruling invalid.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Italian parliament approved changes to Article
513 of the penal code, making testimony given to prosecutors
during investigations invalid as evidence unless it is repeated in
court.
</P>
<P>
The key witness in the case against Craxi, alleged middleman
Silvano Larini, did not testify in any of the three trials.
</P>
<P>
"This ruling is crucially important," said defense lawyer Enzo
Lo Giudice.
</P>
<P>
"It paves the way for similar rulings in the Enimont and
Ambrosiano cases," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
