<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Enhances Supervision of Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Beginning this month, the Central
Bank of the Philippines will examine all banks annually to include
not just their parent companies but their subsidiaries and
affiliates.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Today reported on Friday that the measure,
approved by the central bank's policymaking Monetary Board, is
designed to further strengthen the central banks' supervision of
the banking sector and enhance transparency in the entire system.
</P>
<P>
"We need to see the extent of the exposure of one bank to any
risks," central bank deputy governor Alberto Reyes said, adding
that the central bank can't determine a bank's real level of
exposures and risks because it only looked at the financial
statements submitted by the bank's parent company.
</P>
<P>
The new rule will require central bank examiners to audit the
financial statements of parent banks and their subsidiaries and
affiliates simultaneously in case the banks could hide some of
their non-performing loans (NPLs) in the subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
NPLs are loans that are not paid in three consecutive months,
either in interest or principal. Too much NPLs in the banking
system is the cause of the financial crisis plaguing East and
Southeast Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vehicle Sales Drop to Lowest Level in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Vehicle sales in the first quarter
this year dropped to 23,475 units in the Philippines, the lowest
level since 1994, as a result of the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Journal Friday reported that the figure was 39.4
percent lower than the year-ago level, saying this was a
reflection of the continuing impact of the financial storm and
high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
After the financial crisis began to plague the country last
July, bankers raised lending interest rates to the automotive
industry while reducing loans to customers.
</P>
<P>
Mario de Grano, secretary general of the Chamber of Automotive
Manufacturers of the Philippines, said the biggest drop was
registered by the passenger car sector with a significant 47.2
percent decline to only 11,085 units.
</P>
<P>
Commercial vehicle sales also went down by 30.1 percent as
total sales reached only 12,390 units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
