<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web Site Offers Details on US Companies' Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A Web site unveiled Wednesday
it could put more pressure on U.S. industry to reduce pollution
levels.
</P>
<P>
Assembled by the non-profit Environmental Defense Fund offices
in Oakland, Northern California, the new site allows Americans
with Internet access to locate polluting industries in their
neighborhood, research the amount of chemicals being released and
learn the risk. During its first five hours online, the site which
cost the fund one million dollars and a year of work, received
300,000 hits.
</P>
<P>
The site combines more than 150 government and university
databases onto a single location.
</P>
<P>
One of them is a list of 31,000 manufacturing plants and more
than 700 chemicals. The list, called the Toxic Release Inventory,
came from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, which has
since 1988 required all companies emitting pollutants into the
air, water and solid waste systems to submit annual reports
totaling the amount and type of emissions.
</P>
<P>
Now the new Web site delivers the information in a
user-friendly package. Users can enter the name of any company in
the United States and see whether it has released significant
amounts of pollutants. They can call up maps showing where all
major toxic polluters are in their towns, counties and states.
</P>
<P>
The user also can access rankings of the largest polluters by
any region, and link to peer-reviewed studies spelling out the
health risk of chemicals being released and what type of
government rules affect those chemicals. For major polluters, the
user can click on a form of letter that sends a free fax to the
company's plant manager, informing the firm that the user is aware
of the amount of pollution being put out and requesting that those
levels be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Public pressure has played a big role in urging industries to
reduce their pollution. Big industry, partly because of
accountability and public pressure, has dramatically reduced its
pollution levels over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Defense Fund was founded in 1967 by a group
of scientists and lawyers working to ban DDT. Now the group has
300,000 members, one-fifth of them in California. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
