<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Enjoy Longer Life Expectancy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadians are expecting to live
longer thanks to declines in the mortality rates for the leading
causes of death, Statistics Canada reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Canadian life expectancy at birth reached 81.4 years
for women and 75.5 for men, representing gains of 0.1 and 0.3
years over 1995 respectively.
</P>
<P>
And the gap in life expectancy at birth between men and women
continues to narrow, from 7.5 years in 1978 to 5.7 years in 1996,
the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
For men, the mortality rate declined for all major causes,
including cancer, heart disease, strokes, accidents, suicides and
HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
Yet, "the picture for women was somewhat less favorable," the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
While mortality rates dropped for heart disease, strokes and
accidents, cancer deaths continued to climb, especially lung
cancer. The suicide rate for women also rose in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Cancer and heart disease remained the two leading causes of
death in Canada, accounting for over half of all deaths in 1996.
</P>
<P>
They were followed by strokes, which accounted for seven
percent of all deaths.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
