<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 16 (Xinhua) -- New Romanian government might
negotiate a new loan agreement with International Monetary Fund
(IMF), during talks with Poul Thomsen, IMF chief negotiator for
Romania, Minister of Finance Daniel Daianu told the press
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thomsen is expected in Bucharest next week. The current loan
agreement between Romania and IMF is to close in May, Daianu said.
The stand-by loan agreement was approved by IMF, on May 22, 1997,
for a 13 month period.
</P>
<P>
The loan is divided in five instalments. These instalments are
to be delivered only if economic and legislative criteria are
satisfied. So far, Romania has drawn two instalments. Late last
year, a political crisis occurred in Romania, and negotiations
with IMF were suspended.
</P>
<P>
Thomsen's February's visit to Romania ended without result.
Thomsen stated then that IMF's mission was to come back when
Romanian authorities would have a clear economic program.
</P>
<P>
Romania's new Prime Minister Radu Vasile declared IMF mission
was expected in Bucharest after Easter Holidays.  
