<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Calls for Africa's Debt Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday called on creditor countries to covert into
grants all the remaining official bilateral debt of the poorest
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was included in his 21-page report on Africa
submitted to the Security Council here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Africa's external debt totaled 328.9 billion U.S. dollars in
1995 alone, of which about 45 percent was owed to official
bilateral sources, 30 percent to official multilateral sources and
25 percent to commercial lenders, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Annan also urged creditors to consider clearing the entire debt
stock of the poorest African states as requested by the
Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that the next summit of the group of
industrialized countries consider eliminating trade barriers to
African products.
</P>
<P>
He requested that the Security Council meet every two years at
the ministerial level to assess efforts undertaken and actions
needed to support peace and development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The council, he said, should consider convening a summit-level
session for the same purpose within five years.
</P>
<P>
The council requested at its session last September that the
secretary-general make a report to analyze the causes of African
conflict and to recommend ways of keeping peace and sustaining
development in the continent.
</P>
<P>
It will debate the report Friday next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
