<DOCNO> XIE19980417.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Wants Discussion with Reno on Whitewater Witness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr Thursday asked for a meeting with Attorney General Janet
Reno to resolve issues about a possible conflict of interest
between Starr and a key Whitewater witness.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Reno, Starr said both he and the Justice
Department may appear to have a conflict of interest if they
launch an investigation into whether Arkansas attorney David Hale
"received cash and other gratuities from individuals seeking to
discredit the president."
</P>
<P>
He said he has ideas for "alternate mechanisms" for
investigation, which he would like to discuss with Reno.
</P>
<P>
Hale, who ran a firm that handled Small Business Administration
loans, said then-Governor Bill Clinton pressured him into making
an improper loan that benefited the governor and his business
partners.
</P>
<P>
His testimony was key to the convictions of former Arkansas
Governor Jim Guy Tucker and Clinton's friends.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. attorney in Arkansas had conducted an investigation into
media reports that Hale received cash payments from wealthy
conservative publisher and Clinton foe Richard Mellon Scaife from
1994 to 1996. But last week, Reno's deputy attorney general, Eric
Holder, told Starr a probe of the allegations must, by law, be
done by the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, in an effort to avoid the appearance of
conflict of interest, Starr withdrew from a post being held open
for him at Pepperdine University because it was largely funded by
Scaife.
</P>
<P>
Holder advised Starr in a letter last week that he could refer
the investigation back to the Justice Department if he deemed
there were a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
In today's letter to Reno, Starr said, "all FBI-supervised
contacts" between Hale and the man who allegedly made the payments
occurred before he became independent counsel in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
But Starr said after reviewing the allegations, he concluded
that any investigation by his office "may involve at most the
appearance of a conflict of interest."
</P>
<P>
Starr said conflicts would arise in any Justice Department Hale
probe because the department is by law banned from investigating
the independent counsel's office, because Hale provided
"information damaging to the president of the United States," and
because department officials supervised the FBI agents prior to
August 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
