<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends Permit for Iraq's Import of Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday recommended that Iraq be allowed to import 300
million U.S. dollars worth of oil facilities to promote its oil
export capacity.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the Security Council of the United Nations,
the secretary-general said Iraq's oil facilities have been
dilapidated and even if emergency repairs were carried out, it can
only export 3 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over any six
months in 1998, far less than the 5.2 billion dollars agreed by
the Security Council under the new "oil-for-food" program.
</P>
<P>
Annan also recommended the Security Council lower Iraq's oil
export allowance to 4 billion, beginning in June and ending in
December, and review the sum again later in the year, depending on
the arrival of the needed equipment.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief's recommendations were based on the report by a
group of U.N. oil experts who visited Iraq in March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
