<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Party Pledges Job Creation, Tax Cut, Social </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party Thursday pledged to push
forward major tax and social welfare reforms and to attach top
priority to combating the country's record-high unemployment after
winning the general elections in September this year.
</P>
<P>
In an economic program presented by CDU politician and German
Transport Minister Matthias Wissmann, the CDU stressed that it
would hold on to its ambitious 30 billion mark (16 billion U.S.
dollar) tax cut package which was foiled by the main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD) last year.
</P>
<P>
If it won the September elections, the CDU would also seek to
reduce the social security contributions from the current level of
42 percent to below 40 percent within four years, Wissmann said.
</P>
<P>
The top priority for the party's future economic policy would
be job creation, Wissmann told a news conference in Bonn Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the current economic upswing, Germany's unemployment
has been hovering at record levels of around 4.8 million for more
than one year and has become a major rebuff for Kohl's ruling
party which has been in power since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Apart from tax and social welfare reforms, the CDU Thursday
also proposed a number of other measures to help create jobs,
including more state assistance to small- and medium-sized
enterprises and high-tech companies, and to encourage young people
to take risks to found their businesses.
</P>
<P>
Local communities were also called upon to create jobs for all
social welfare recipients in a bid to reduce their dependence on
the state.
</P>
<P>
Despite their policy differences, both the CDU and the SPD have
chosen unemployment as the top issue for their election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the SPD is due to hold a one-day party congress in
the eastern German city of Leipzig to formally endorse Gerhard
Schroeder as the party's chancellor candidate and to adopt the
party's election platform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
