<HEADLINE> Jones to Appeal Case Against Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Paula Corbin Jones said
Thursday she will appeal a federal judge's decision to dismiss her
sexual harassment lawsuit against U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Jones made the announcement at a news conference called by her
attorneys in Dallas, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
Jones said she was "shocked" by U.S. District Judge Susan
Webber Wright's decision to dismiss the suit on April 1.
</P>
<P>
Jones alleged that Clinton propositioned her in a hotel room in
Little Rock, Arkansas, in 1991, when he was governor and she was a
state employee. She said she refused his advances and that her
career suffered as a result. The president strongly denies the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
Jones said her attorneys advised her that there are "very
strong" grounds to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Wright dismissed the case, saying that even if Jones's
allegations are true, she failed to prove she had been materially
damaged by rebuffing Clinton's advances.
</P>
<P>
The president's supporters anticipated the appeal. "We are
confident that the appellate court will not permit Paula Jones and
her supporters to pursue this case," Clinton's attorney, Robert S.
Bennett, said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
"It is unfortunate that our legal system can nonetheless
continued to be abused by Mrs. Jones' political and financial
supporters who wish to harm the president," Bennett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
